 de Avellaneda|Racing Club]]\n| manageryears2  = 2006\u20132007\n| managerclubs2  = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]]\n| manageryears3  = 2007\u20132008\n| managerclubs3  = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n| manageryears4  = 2009\u20132010\n| managerclubs4  = [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]]\n| manageryears5  = 2011\n| managerclubs5  = [[Calcio Catania|Catania]]\n| manageryears6  = 2011\n| managerclubs6  = [[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing Club]]\n| manageryears7  = 2011\u2013\n| managerclubs7  = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ARG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1991 Chile]]|[[Argentina national football team|Team]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993 Ecuador]]|[[Argentina national football team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[King Fahd Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[1992 King Fahd Cup|1992 Saudi Arabia]]|[[Argentina national football team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[1996 Olympic Games|1996 Atlanta]]|[[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Diego Pablo Simeone Gonz\u00e1lez''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8dje\u0263o \u02c8pa\u03b2lo sime\u02c8one}}; {{IPA-it|\u02c8dje\u02d0\u0261o sime\u02c8o\u02d0ne}}; born 28 April 1970), also known as '''El Cholo''' ({{IPA-es|el \u02c8t\u0283olo|}}), is an Argentine [[association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former player, who played as a [[midfielder]]; he has been the manager of [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] since December 2011. Simeone is often considered to be a legendary figure in the history of Atl\u00e9tico Madrid, due to his achievements as a player and manager with them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://a.msn.com/01/fr-be/AAxhbXF|title=Diego Simeone - a legend of the Calderon|website=MSN|language=fr-BE|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2672242-origins-of-el-cholo-remembering-diego-simeones-atletico-madrid-playing-career|title=Origins of El Cholo: Remembering Diego Simeone's Atl\u00e9tico Madrid Playing Career|last=Jones|first=Mark|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/mar/01/diego-simeone-atletico-madrid-real-madrid-derby-la-liga|title=Diego Simeone leads Atl\u00e9tico Madrid with passion into derby with Real {{!}} Sid Lowe|last=Lowe|first=Sid|date=1 March 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 December 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn his club career that started in 1987, Simeone played in Argentina, Italy, and Spain for [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]], [[A.C. Pisa 1909|Pisa]], [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], [[Inter Milan]], [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] and [[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing Club]]. He won a [[Double (association football)#Spain|domestic double]] with Atl\u00e9tico Madrid in 1996, and the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] with Inter in [[1998 UEFA Cup Final|1998]], also winning another [[Double (association football)#Italy|domestic double]] with Lazio in 2000, as well as the [[1999 UEFA Super Cup]] and the [[2000 Supercoppa Italiana]]. Simeone was [[Cap (sports)|capped]] over [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100]] times for the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]] and represented the country at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]], [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]] and [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s, and in four editions of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]], winning the tournament in [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1991]] and [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993]]. He also won the [[King Fahd Cup]] in [[1992 King Fahd Cup|1992]], and a silver medal at the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Summer Olympic games]].\n\nAs a manager, Simeone has coached Argentine sides Racing Club, [[Estudiantes de La Plata]], [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]], [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] and Italian club [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] before joining Spanish club Atl\u00e9tico Madrid in 2011. He won the [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] both with Estudiantes and River Plate, and has had his biggest managerial success with Atl\u00e9tico Madrid, winning La Liga, the [[Copa del Rey]], two [[UEFA Europa League]]s, two [[UEFA Super Cup]]s, and also being runner-up of the [[UEFA Champions League]] twice.\n\n==Club career==\n[[File:Simeone 1987.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Simeone with [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]] in 1987]]\nWhen Simeone was 14, his youth coach [[Victorio Spinetto]] nicknamed him \"''[[Cholo]]''\", as his energetic play reminded him of former [[Boca Juniors]] player and Argentine international [[Carmelo Simeone]] (no relation) who possessed the nickname.<ref name=\"ole.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ole.com.ar/diario/2002/06/05/m-397561.htm |title=Jens Fjellstr\u00f6m ny tr\u00e4nare i Malm\u00f6 FF (Jens Fjellstr\u00f6m new coach in Malm\u00f6 FF) |publisher=aftonbladet.se |date=26 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAfter starting his career with [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]], Simeone moved to Italian [[Serie A]] club [[A.C. Pisa 1909|Pisa]] in 1990. The club was relegated in his [[1990\u201391 Serie A|first season]] and, after it failed to gain promotion the [[1991\u201392 Serie B|following year]], Simeone was sold to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the Spanish [[La Liga]]. Simeone played two seasons in Seville, after which he was signed by [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]. At Atl\u00e9tico, he was part of the team which won the [[Double (association football)|double]] of the [[List of Spanish football champions|Liga title]] and [[1995\u201396 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] during the [[1995\u201396 La Liga|1995\u201396 season]].\n\nIn 1997, Simeone returned to Serie A with [[Inter Milan]] and played two full seasons, winning the [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup]] in a side spearheaded by [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] up front. In 1999, Simeone joined fellow Argentines [[N\u00e9stor Sensini]], [[Mat\u00edas Almeyda]], [[Hern\u00e1n Crespo]] and [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]] at [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]]'s [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]. The side had gone close to the ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]'' in the season before Simeone's arrival and he helped deliver the championship after [[1999\u20132000 Serie A|a season]], where [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] led the standings by two points going into the last day. A Juve loss at rainy [[A.C. Perugia Calcio|Perugia]] coupled with Lazio's comfortable home win over [[Urbs Sportiva Reggina 1914|Reggina]] at the [[Stadio Olimpico]] ensured Simeone's first Serie A title. After winning the double in Spain, he would then add the Italian double as Lazio edged out Inter to claim the [[1999\u20132000 Coppa Italia]].\n\nHe went on to play three more seasons in Rome, which included more last day drama as Simeone's goal against former club Inter on the last day of the [[2001\u201302 Serie A|2001\u201302 campaign]] effectively ruined his old employers' title dream.\n\nSimeone returned to Atl\u00e9tico Madrid in 2003, spending his next two seasons there. In total, he played in 165 matches for Atl\u00e9tico, scoring 31 goals. In 2005, he left Europe to finish his playing career in Argentina with [[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing Club]].\n\n==International career==\nIn 1992, Simeone represented the Argentina under-23 team at the [[1992 CONMEBOL Pre-Olympic Tournament]] in Paraguay, which saw Argentina fail to qualify for the 1992 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/argentina-v-bolivia-02-february-1992-243429/|title=Argentina v Bolivia, 02 February 1992|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina senior team]], Simeone amassed [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|106 caps]],<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/arg-recintlp.html |title=RSSSF Argentine international players |publisher=Rsssf.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr4olopA?url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/arg-recintlp.html |archivedate=17 January 2010}}</ref> the first coming in 1988.\n\nSimeone won the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica 1991|1991]] and [[Copa Am\u00e9rica 1993|1993]] editions of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] with Argentina. He played in the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]], [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]] and [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s. He was a member of the team that won the silver medal at the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]], Georgia, as one of the three over-23 players allowed per squad. As a midfielder, Simeone scored 11 goals for his country, including one in the [[1992 King Fahd Cup Final|final]] of the [[1992 King Fahd Cup]].\n[[File:Argentina seleccion 1991.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Simeone (second from left, lower row) with the Argentina squad that won the [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] held in Chile]]\nDuring the 1998 World Cup, [[England national football team|England]]'s [[David Beckham]] was sent off for kicking Simeone in retaliation for a foul (see also [[Argentina\u2013England football rivalry]]). Simeone later said he simulated the injury from the kick in order to get Beckham sent off.<ref>{{cite news | title=England v Argentina \u2013 A history | work=Observer Sport Monthly, 19 May 2002| url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2002/countries/story/0,,716632,00.html | accessdate=15 November 2006 | location=London | first=John | last=Carlin | date=19 May 2002}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' was critical of the Argentinian's theatrics in that incident, stating Simeone first delivered a \"heavy-handed challenge\" on Beckham and then \"fell like a ton of bricks\" when Beckham retaliated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup/news/1998/07/04/philjones_04/ |title=CNN/SI \u2013 World Cup France '98 \u2013 The Netherlands pay back controversial loss to Argentina \u2013 Saturday July 04, 1998 03:33&nbsp;pm |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date=4 July 1998 }}</ref> In the following match, against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], Simeone was injured by a tackle from [[Arthur Numan]] during his team's defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup/news/1998/07/04/netherlands_optional/ |title=CNN/SI \u2013 World Cup France '98 \u2013 Bergkamp scores in 90th minute to lead the Netherlands to victory \u2013 Wednesday September 16, 1998 05:34&nbsp;pm |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date=16 September 1998 }}</ref> In the 2002 World Cup, his last, Argentina was eliminated in the group stage, which included a 1\u20130 loss to England in which Beckham converted a penalty.\n\nSimeone said he was \"embarrassed\" at having surpassed [[Diego Maradona]] as Argentina's most capped player, though Simeone has since been surpassed by [[Roberto Ayala]], [[Javier Mascherano]], [[Javier Zanetti]] and [[Lionel Messi]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" />\n\n==Style of play==\nSimeone was regarded as a tenacious, versatile, hard-working and complete two-way [[midfielder]] who was mobile, good in the air and capable both of winning balls and starting attacking plays, also having a penchant for scoring several goals himself. This enabled him to play anywhere in midfield throughout his career, although he was usually deployed in the [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|centre]] in a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box]] or [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfield]] role.<ref name=\"Unlike Simeone's Atletico, Seedorf's AC Milan still searching for identity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/blog/tactics-and-analysis/67/post/1839846/cox-unlike-simeones-atletico-seedorfs-milan-searching-for-identity|title=Unlike Simeone's Atletico, Seedorf's AC Milan still searching for identity|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Michael Cox|date=10 March 2014|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/news/lazio-simeone-io-in-panchina-prima-o-poi-419307|title=Lazio:{{!}} Simeone 'Io in panchina? Prima o poi...'|publisher=Calcio Mercato|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/04-05-2016/simeone-origini-cholo-pisa-catania-inter-lazio-leader-nato-150477342874.shtml|title=Simeone, alle origini del Cholo: da Pisa a Catania, dall'Inter alla Lazio leader nato|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Marco Fallisi|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> He was also used in an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|offensive midfield]] role on occasion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcinter1908.it/copertina/bergomi-simeone-e-rimasto-nel-cuore-degli-interisti-puo-tornare-ma/ |title=Bergomi: \u201cLippi cacci\u00f2 Simeone, nessuno cap\u00ec. Per tornare nell\u2019Inter di ora serve coraggio\u201d |publisher=F.C. Inter 1908 |language=Italian |last1=Parrone |first1=Francesco |date=28 May 2016 |accessdate=26 October 2019 }}</ref> A talented yet combative player, he was primarily known for his leadership, tactical versatility, intelligence, strength and stamina,<ref name=\"as.com\">{{cite web|url=http://as.com/videos/2014/08/01/portada/1406917590_027555.html|title=Diego Simeone juntaba garra, car\u00e1cter y una gran t\u00e9cnica|publisher=AS.com|language=Spanish|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> although he was also praised by pundits for his technique, vision and passing range.<ref name=\"Unlike Simeone's Atletico, Seedorf's AC Milan still searching for identity\"/><ref name=\"as.com\"/> Simeone once described his style as \"holding a knife between his teeth\".<ref name=\"Unlike Simeone's Atletico, Seedorf's AC Milan still searching for identity\"/> His main inspirations as a player were Brazilian midfielder [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] and German midfielder [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcinternews.it/ex-nerazzurri/simeone-e-le-fonti-di-ispirazioneda-giovane-ammiravo-falcao-poi-ho-cominciato-ad-apprezzare-matthaus-179773|title=Simeone e le fonti di ispirazione:\"Da giovane ammiravo Falc\u00e3o, poi ho cominciato ad apprezzare Matth\u00e4us\"|publisher=F.C. Inter News|language=Italian|author1=Mattia Zangari|date=17 March 2015|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Early years===\nSimeone ended his playing career for Racing Club, playing his last match on 17 February 2006, and then became manager for the same team. After a rough start, the team made an impressive finish in the 2006 Clausura. When a new club president was elected, Simeone left Racing in May 2006 and was replaced by [[Reinaldo Merlo]].\n\nOn 18 May, Simeone became head coach of [[Estudiantes de La Plata]] and soon led them to their first [[List of Argentine football champions|league title]] in 23 years after defeating Boca Juniors 2\u20131 in a final match played on 13 December 2006. In an October 2006 poll in the sports daily ''[[Ol\u00e9 (sports newspaper)|Ol\u00e9]]'', Simeone was voted as the best manager in the Argentine league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarin.com/diario/2006/10/31/um/m-01300708.htm |title=Simeone, el gran estratega del f\u00fatbol argentino |publisher=Clarin.com |date=31 October 2006 }}</ref> He was also praised as a \"born manager\" by former Argentine international [[Roberto Perfumo]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20080108095141/http://old.ole.clarin.com/jsp/v4/pagina.jsp?pagId=01309221 El t\u00e9cnico se hace, s\u00ed, pero sobre todo nace] </ref> Simeone left Estudiantes after the end of the 2007 Apertura, where Estudiantes was not a contender after a poor start, but had a strong finish of nine games without defeat. On 15 December 2007, Simeone was unveiled as the new [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] coach, succeeding [[Daniel Passarella]]. The contract was reported to be for one year, starting on 3 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/breakingnews/feedstory/0,,-7156071,00.html |title=Guardian football |publisher=Football.guardian.co.uk |date= |location=London }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> After an early elimination in the [[Copa Libertadores]], losing to [[Club Atl\u00e9tico San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] in the second round, Simeone and River Plate went on to win the [[2007\u201308 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n season#Torneo Clausura|2008 Clausura]] championship after beating [[Club Olimpo|Olimpo]] 2\u20131 in the [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Monumental]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/06/09/sports/LA-SPT-SOC-Argentine-Roundup.php |title=River Plate crowned champion of Argentine Clausura \u2013 |publisher=International Herald Tribune |date=29 March 2009 }}</ref> On 7 November 2008, Simeone announced his resignation as coach of River Plate after their elimination in the quarter-finals of the [[2008 Copa Sudamericana]] by Mexican side [[C.D. Guadalajara|Chivas]] and a poor run of form of 11 domestic matches without a win, which left them bottom of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina]] with only six matches remaining.<ref>[http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story?id=744488&s=arg&type=story Diego Simeone renunci\u00f3 a la direcci\u00f3n t\u00e9cnica de River] at [[ESPN Deportes]] {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/fsi/fsla/story/revista?contentId=8792932 |title=Las causas de una salida inevitable |publisher=Msn.foxsports.com |date= }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 15 April 2009, Simeone joined San Lorenzo to replace [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Russo]] following the club's exit in the first round of the [[2009 Copa Libertadores]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=637488&sec=global&cc=5739 |title=Ex-River boss Simeone to manage San Lorenzo |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=16 April 2009 }}</ref> On 3 April 2010, Simeone resigned from San Lorenzo due to poor results and mounting criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=765971&sec=global&cc=5739 |title=Simeone quits San Lorenzo post after dismal run |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=4 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Catania and Racing Club===\nOn 19 January 2011, Simeone flew to [[Sicily]] to join Serie A side [[Calcio Catania|Catania]], replacing [[Marco Giampaolo]], who left the club just hours earlier.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/?action=read&id=248797 |title=ESCLUSIVA TMW \u2013 Criscitiello: \"Colpo Lo Monaco: Simeone a Catania\" |trans-title=TMW EXCLUSIVE \u2013 Criscitiello: \"Lo Monaco strikes: Simeone to Catania\" |work=Tutto Mercato Web |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |language=Italian}}</ref><ref name=\"simeone_catania\">{{cite news|url=http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=21846 |publisher=Calcio Catania |language=Italian |accessdate=19 January 2011 |date=19 January 2011 |title=Diego Pablo Simeone \u00e8 il nuovo allenatore del Catania |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727105119/http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=21846 |archivedate=27 July 2011}}</ref> On 1 June 2011, Simeone left his post after helping Catania stave off relegation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/?action=read&id=271540 |title=Catania, rescinde Simeone |trans-title=Simeone quits Catania |work=Tutto Mercato Web |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |language=Italian}}</ref> On 21 June 2011, Simeone was named as the new coach of Racing Club for a second spell in charge, replacing Miguel \u00c1ngel Russo, who had resigned the week prior.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.racingclub.com.ar/detalle/noticias/2789/ |title=Diego Simeone fue presentado como nuevo t\u00e9cnico de Racing Club |trans-title=Diego Simeone was introduced as new coach of Racing Club |work=[[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing]] |date=21 June 2011 |accessdate=21 June 2011 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625133750/http://www.racingclub.com.ar/detalle/noticias/2789 |archivedate=25 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\n====2011\u201312: First Europa League triumph====\nOn 23 December 2011, Simeone was unveiled as the new [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] coach, succeeding [[Gregorio Manzano]], who had been dismissed the day before following defeat to third-tier [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]] in the [[Copa del Rey]]. His first game as Atl\u00e9tico manager was a 0\u20130 away draw against [[Manuel Pellegrini]]'s [[Malaga CF|Malaga]]. His first season ended with the team winning the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] by beating [[Athletic Bilbao]] 3\u20130 in the [[2012 UEFA Europa League Final|final]] in [[Bucharest]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://eurosport.yahoo.com/09052012/58/europa-league-falcao-inspires-atletico-europa-crown.html |title=Europa League \u2013 Falcao inspires Atletico to Europa crown |work=[[EuroSport]] |date=9 May 2012 |access-date=9 May 2012 |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |last=Quarrell |first=Dan |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716185450/http://eurosport.yahoo.com/news/matchpack-atletico-madrid-v-athletic-174907897.html |archive-date=16 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313: Copa del Rey and European Super Cup victories====\nOn 31 August 2012, his Atl\u00e9tico side won the [[2012 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] after defeating [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 4\u20131 at the [[Stade Louis II]] in Monaco. In the [[2012-13 La Liga|domestic league]], the team made an impressive start to the season, finishing the first half in second place, behind only Barcelona and above city rivals Real Madrid. Eventually, Simeone led the team to a third-place finish in the league, which at the time was the best finish in 17 years for Atl\u00e9tico. On 17 May 2013, he won the [[2012\u201313 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] after Atl\u00e9tico defeated rivals [[Real Madrid C.F|Real Madrid]] 2\u20131 at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]].\n\n====2013\u201314: La Liga win and first Champions League final====\n[[File:Atl\u00e9tico de Madrid, Liga 2013-2014 (Mayo 2014),.JPG|thumb|Atl\u00e9tico Madrid celebrates after winning the [[2013\u201314 La Liga]]]]\nAtl\u00e9tico began the [[2013\u201314 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2013\u201314 season]] with a similar squad to their prior season, despite selling star player [[Radamel Falcao]] to [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] for a reported \u20ac60&nbsp;million fee and acquiring [[David Villa]] from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on a free transfer. While the season began with a defeat to ''Bar\u00e7a'' in the [[2013 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], the team recorded eight-straight victories in [[2013\u201314 La Liga|La Liga]], the best league start in club history. This included a 1\u20130 away win at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u against Real Madrid, making Simeone the first Atl\u00e9tico manager since [[Claudio Ranieri]] in 1999 to record a league victory there. Atl\u00e9tico finished the first half of the season in first place in La Liga, level on points with Barcelona at 47. In [[Barcelona 1\u20131 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid (May 2014)|the last round of the season]], on 17 May, Atl\u00e9tico needed at least a draw in the [[Camp Nou]] against Barcelona to be crowned champions for the first time since 1996, while a loss would give the title to Barcelona. A [[Diego God\u00edn]] header from a corner kick in the 48th minute gave Atl\u00e9tico an equaliser and the draw they needed to win their tenth league title and first since 1996, when Simeone himself was an Atl\u00e9tico player.\n\nSimeone became the second Argentine manager after [[Helenio Herrera]] to hand Atl\u00e9tico a Spanish championship, and the second manager after [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]] to win it both as a player and as a coach of the team. Under Simeone, Atl\u00e9tico collected 90 points in La Liga, surpassing its 1996 record of 87, making the 2013\u201314 season the most successful in club history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Richard|title=Barcelona 1 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid 1, La Liga: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/la-liga/10838338/Barcelona-v-Atletico-Madrid-La-Liga-live.html|accessdate=17 May 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2013\u201314, Atl\u00e9tico finished top of their [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group and qualified for the quarter-finals with a 5\u20131 aggregate win over [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in the round of 16. This was the first time they had reached the Champions League quarter-finals since [[1996\u201397 UEFA Champions League|1996\u201397]], when Simeone played for the team. In the quarter-finals, Atl\u00e9tico defeated Barcelona 2\u20131 on aggregate from Simeone's tactic of cutting the swift-passing midfield of Barcelona in two, thus denying them space and isolating [[Xavi]] and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] from forwards Lionel Messi and [[Neymar]]. In the semi-finals, Atl\u00e9tico defeated [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]'s Chelsea 3\u20131 at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] following a goalless draw at home to reach the [[2014 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]] for only the second time in club history, the first being in [[1974 European Cup Final|1974]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/apr/30/chelsea-atletico-madrid-champions-league-match-report|title=Chelsea bow out to superior firepower of Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|date=30 April 2014|work=Guardian|accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref> Atl\u00e9tico was the only undefeated team in the Champions League prior to the final, recording nine wins and three draws, and had the best defence in the competition, conceding only 6 goals in 12 matches.\n\nIn the [[2014 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] on 24 May 2014, Atl\u00e9tico faced [[Madrid Derby|city rivals]] Real Madrid at the [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz]] in [[Lisbon]]. Despite leading from Diego God\u00edn's header, Atl\u00e9tico conceded a late equaliser in the 93rd minute of the match. The goal hampered Atl\u00e9tico's morale, and the team ended up losing 4\u20131 after extra time, with Simeone losing the opportunity to be the third Argentine coach to win the Champions League, after [[Luis Carniglia]] and Helenio Herrera. After the final goal, Real Madrid's [[Rapha\u00ebl Varane]] kicked the ball towards Simeone, causing Simeone to run onto the pitch in anger. He was sent to the stands, and Varane was booked for the incident. Reflecting, Simeone said, \"I also made a mistake with my reaction. He's a young guy with a bright future.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Simeone squares up to Varane|url=http://www.marca.com/2014/05/25/en/football/spanish_football/1400974294.html|accessdate=25 May 2014|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=25 May 2014}}</ref> Simeone also admitted a mistake in selecting striker [[Diego Costa]] to start the match, as he had been recently injured and was forced off after eight minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Atletico Madrid: Simeone admits to mistake over injured Costa|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27562716|accessdate=3 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315====\nIn the summer of 2014, Chelsea acquired [[Diego Costa]], [[Filipe Lu\u00eds]] and [[Thibaut Courtois]] from Atl\u00e9tico, and also David Villa moved to the [[Major League Soccer|MLS]]. In response, Atl\u00e9tico acquired striker [[Mario Mand\u017euki\u0107]] from [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], goalkeeper [[Jan Oblak]] from [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] and forwards [[Antoine Griezmann]] from [[Real Sociedad]] and [[\u00c1ngel Correa]] from [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]], and recover young midfielder [[Sa\u00fal \u00d1\u00edguez|Sa\u00fal]] who was on loan at [[Rayo Vallecano]]. The season started with Atl\u00e9tico defeating city rivals Real Madrid for the [[2014 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Spanish Super Cup]] in August and repeating the previous year's victory in the Bernab\u00e9u for the league in September. In January, the team acquired [[Fernando Torres]] on loan from Milan. However, Atl\u00e9tico finished the league in third place and was eliminated in the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] quarter-finals by Real Madrid 1\u20130, on aggregate.\n\n====2015\u201316: Defensive records and second Champions League final====\nBefore the start of the season, Filipe Lu\u00eds returned from Chelsea with the team also acquiring Montenegrin defender [[Stefan Savi\u0107]] and Belgian midfielder [[Yannick Carrasco]]. Mario Mand\u017euki\u0107 left for [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. In 2015\u201316, Atl\u00e9tico was the team with the best defensive record in Europe's \"big five\" leagues, only allowing 18 goals scored against them in 38 La Liga games. Atl\u00e9tico was also the team with the most clean sheets in their games. The team was contending the [[2015\u201316 La Liga|league title]] until the last fixture against Barcelona and Real Madrid, settling for third with 88 points. \n\nIn the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], Simeone led Atl\u00e9tico to their second Champions League final in three seasons, becoming the first Argentine manager since [[H\u00e9ctor C\u00faper]] to reach two Champions League finals. Atl\u00e9tico had defeated [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] on penalties during the round of 16, beat defending champions Barcelona 3\u20132 on aggregate and favourites Bayern Munich 2\u20132, going through on away goals, setting up a repeat of the 2014 final again facing Real Madrid. The match ended 1\u20131 after extra time leading to a penalty shootout. [[Juanfran (footballer, born 1985)|Juanfran]] was the only player to miss his kick, enabling [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] to score Real's last spot kick, condemning Atl\u00e9tico to a second Champions League final defeat in three seasons.\n\n====2016\u201317====\nIn the summer of 2016, Atl\u00e9tico purchased forward [[Kevin Gameiro]] from [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], midfielder [[Nicol\u00e1s Gait\u00e1n]] from Benfica, defender [[\u0160ime Vrsaljko]] from [[U.S. Sassuolo|Sassuolo]]. They also acquired the rights to Fernando Torres (previously on loan from Milan). The team again finished third in the [[2016\u201317 La Liga|league]] and lost in the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] semi-finals, again to Real Madrid.\n\n====2017\u201318: Second Europa League triumph====\nOn 5 September 2017, Simeone extended his contract with Atl\u00e9tico for two more years, until June 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=Diego Simeone: Atletico Madrid manager signs two-year contract extension|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41161373|work=BBC Sport|date=5 September 2017}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2017\u201318 season]], Atl\u00e9tico would finish in second place in La Liga, behind Barcelona but ahead of city rivals Real Madrid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-spain/atletico-clinch-second-spot-bale-leads-real-rout-idUKKCN1ID0SS|title=Atletico clinch second spot, Bale leads Real rout|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.K.|access-date=18 May 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Atl\u00e9tico did not advance and dropped to the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League]]. In January 2018, Diego Costa returned to Atl\u00e9tico from Chelsea. On 16 May 2018, the team won the [[2018 UEFA Europa League Final]] against [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Malag\u00f3n |first=Manuel |title=Simeone gana su sexto t\u00edtulo como t\u00e9cnico del Atl\u00e9tico |url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/atletico/2018/05/16/5afc6a92e5fdeab9488b45f1.html |date=16 May 2018 |access-date=16 May 2018 |newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |publisher=[[Unidad Editorial]] Informaci\u00f3n Deportiva, S.L.U. |language=es}}</ref> Simeone was sent to the stands in the first leg of the semi-finals against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and was suspended. He was forced to watch the second leg and final from the stands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/atletico-madrid/story/3483214/diego-simeone-handed-europa-league-final-touchline-ban|title=Simeone banned from Europa final touchline|work=ESPN.com|access-date=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319====\nIn the 2018\u201319 season, Atl\u00e9tico bought [[Thomas Lemar]] from [[AS Monaco]]<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2708864-thomas-lemar-transfer-agreement-with-atletico-madrid-announced-by-monaco</ref> and [[Rodri (footballer, born 1996)|Rodri]] from [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]<ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/breaking-rodri-completes-628million-transfer-17389172</ref>, and in January 2019 acquired [[\u00c1lvaro Morata]] on loan from Chelsea<ref>https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11668/11620554/alvaro-morata-joins-atletico-madrid-from-chelsea-on-loan</ref>, while longtime team captain Gabi signed for Qatari club [[Al-Sadd SC|Al-Sadd]] before the start of the season.<ref>https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/atletico-captain-gabi-agrees-to-join-qatar-s-al-sadd</ref> The team again finished second in the [[2018\u201319 La Liga|league]] behind Barcelona and ahead of city rivals Real Madrid. In the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], they advanced to the first knockout round, where they were eliminated by [[Juventus]], winning the first leg 2\u20130 at the [[Wanda Metropolitano]] but losing the return leg 3\u20130 in Turin.\n\n====2019-2020====\nSimeone guided his side into the last 16 of [[UEFA Champions League]] for the sixth time since he came to reign in 2011, while before his arrival [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atl\u00e9tico]] had only done so 7 times in 60 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://amp.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/12/12/5df2969422601d85748b4649.html|title=Simeone's Long Lasting Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|publisher=MARCA|date=12 December 2019}}</ref> On 11 March 2020, Atletico Madrid eliminated the reigning European champions Liverpool with a 3-2 triumph at [[Anfield]], winning 4-2 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51800660|title=Liverpool 2-3 Atletico Madrid (2-4 agg): Holders out of Champions League|date=11 March 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=11 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Tactics==\nSimeone's preferred formation is the [[4\u20134\u20132]], which he first practiced when he was manager of [[Estudiantes de la Plata]] in 2006. In this formation, the two wingers move inside and act like attacking midfielders, creating space for the full backs and fluidity in the attack, effectively being a 4\u20132\u20132\u20132 when the team is on the offensive. The two holding midfielders provide the defensive muscle needed to win midfield battles. Utilizing this formation, Simeone's Estudiantes won the [[2006\u201307 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|2006 Apertura]] by beating [[Boca Juniors]] 2\u20131 while being down to ten men from the first half. It is essentially this formation that Simeone also utilizes at Atl\u00e9tico Madrid. Simeone has listed his coaching influences being [[Marcelo Bielsa]], [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]], [[Alfio Basile]], [[Victorio Spinetto]], [[Luigi Simoni]], [[Carlos Bilardo]] and [[Radomir Anti\u0107]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2016/07/04/investigating-the-origins-of-cholismo/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929000510/https://thesefootballtimes.co/2016/07/04/investigating-the-origins-of-cholismo/ |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhen he was manager at River Plate, a team graced with the attacking talents of [[Radamel Falcao]], [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]], [[Ariel Ortega]], [[Mauro Rosales]], [[Diego Buonanotte]], [[Augusto Fern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Sebasti\u00e1n Abreu]], Simeone played an aggressive 3\u20133\u20131\u20133 formation reminiscent of those used by influential manager (and Simeone's mentor) [[Marcelo Bielsa]].<ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/how-finishing-bottom-argentine-league-8062543</ref> Using this formation, River won the [[2007\u201308 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|2008 Clausura]], but in the next season, with S\u00e1nchez having returned to [[Udinese]] and several players suffering from injuries, the 3\u20133\u20131\u20133 backfired and River finished bottom of the table, with Simeone being sacked in the process.<ref>\u2013https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/how-finishing-bottom-argentine-league-8062543</ref>\n\nA common feature of Simeone's teams is defensive compactness and quick counter-attacks. Their defending consists of two stages: deep defending in their own defensive third in a narrow 4\u20134\u20132 consisting of two closely connected defensive lines of four players, and counter-pressing in their opponents' third to win the ball high up the pitch. When the ball is won, the team attack as a unit, deploying their fluid 4\u20132\u20132\u20132 formation, with the forwards often shifting to the flanks to create even more space.<ref>http://www.zonalmarking.net/2015/02/10/atletico-madrid-4-0-real-madrid-atletico-solid-in-central-areas-when-defending-and-fluid-to-cause-overloads-out-wide-when-attacking/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5j6ZT_NFJ8U</ref> In defense, the key idea is to force opponents into wide areas, gain numerical dominance in the ball's zone and steal the ball or force the opponent into a backward pass.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5j6ZT_NFJ8U</ref> Counter-pressing consists of reducing an opposing team's space, disrupting their build-up and reducing the number of \"safe\" positions for opponents' movement on the pitch, thus eliminating goal threats.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5j6ZT_NFJ8U</ref> [[Claudio Ranieri]]'s [[Premier League]]-winning [[2015-16 Leicester City F.C. season|2015-16 Leicester City]] team has been compared to Simeone's Atletico Madrid for upsetting bigger teams by also playing a narrow 4\u20134\u20132 and being compact in defense and midfield.<ref>http://www.goal.com/en/news/1862/premier-league/2016/04/27/22851442/filipe-luis-leicester-are-like-atletico</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/apr/07/atletico-madrid-title-win-leicester-president</ref>\n\nIn the short time he managed Italian side Catania in 2011, he switched between a 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 and a 4\u20133\u20131\u20132 in order to bring out the best from playmaker [[Adri\u00e1n Ricchiuti]] while employing many of the counter-attacking features that would later become his trademark at Atl\u00e9tico. Ricchiuti was tasked with linking the midfield and attack and creating chances for whichever of [[Maxi L\u00f3pez]], [[Gonzalo Bergessio]] and [[Francesco Lodi]] were selected up front. Simeone said he did not want to \u201cfossilise [himself] with a rigid tactic,\u201d saying managers cannot have a favourite formation \u201cfor the simple fact that we have to adapt not to what we like but to what we have to work with\u201d.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/these-football-times/2019/feb/20/diego-simeone-italy-catania-atletico-madrid</ref> His players stayed compact and narrow when defending, with the widemen \u2013 two of [[Ezequiel Schelotto]], [[Giuseppe Mascara]], [[Raphael Martinho]] and [[Papu G\u00f3mez|Alejandro G\u00f3mez]] \u2013 expected to drop back and tuck in when out of possession; meanwhile, playmaker Ricchiuti and the central striker \u2013 more often than not L\u00f3pez \u2013 moved back into midfield rather than pressing the centre-backs, with the aim being preventing simple passes into the middle of the pitch.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/these-football-times/2019/feb/20/diego-simeone-italy-catania-atletico-madrid</ref>\n\nSimeone is also renowned for his attention to detail and quick adaptability to a game's changing situations. During his time as manager of Atl\u00e9tico Madrid, he has placed emphasis on creating chances from set-pieces, while not allowing the opponent to create chances from set-pieces. Several important goals, including the one that gave Atl\u00e9tico the 2014 La Liga title, have been scored from set-pieces.<ref>http://www.zonalmarking.net/2014/05/19/barcelona-1-1-atletico-simeones-side-seal-historic-title-victory-at-the-camp-nou/</ref> While his teams aren't known for controlling possession, they are lauded for controlling the pace and space in which a game is played. He is quick in making tactical changes to influence a game's outcome. In the [[2015-16 UEFA Champions League]] semi-final against Bayern in Munich, with his team down 1\u20130 after 45 minutes, he moved [[Sa\u00fal \u00d1\u00edguez]] from the right wing to a holding midfielder position, changing the 4\u20134\u20132 to a 4\u20131\u20134\u20131 formation with [[Yannick Carrasco|Carrasco]] and Griezmann on the flanks. While on paper Sa\u00fal was seemingly out of his normal position in this role, in effect this change meant that midfielders [[Gabi (footballer)|Gabi]] and [[Koke (footballer, born 1992)|Koke]], who were overwhelmed in the first half by Bayern's pressure, would now be shielded by Sa\u00fal's presence behind them, and the midfield would regain its much-needed composure. Eventually, the change had the desired outcome, with Atl\u00e9tico equalizing through [[Antoine Griezmann]] and advancing to the Champions League final.<ref>http://www.football-lineups.com/match/235316/</ref><ref>http://www.zonalmarking.net/2016/05/05/atletico-madrid-2-2-bayern-munich-atletico-progress-on-away-goals/</ref>\n\nSimeone has also earned praise for instilling confidence and discipline in his players, which has helped his teams emerge victorious under adverse conditions. For example, in the last game of 2014's La Liga, at the [[Camp Nou]] against Barcelona, when Atl\u00e9tico needed a draw to win the championship, both [[Diego Costa]] and [[Arda Turan]] were taken out of the game due to injury in the first half, and Barcelona opened the scoring. However, Simeone was able to rally his team at half-time and Godin's header in the second half gave them the much needed draw. Simeone said: \"At half-time I told them to be relaxed. In the first half we did well. I knew if we scored, it would cost them. That's what happened. There was an amazing collective effort from everyone.\"<ref>http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2014/05/17/4824696/simeone-im-sure-aragones-was-defending-with-us</ref> During a leg in the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League]] semi-final against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]], Atl\u00e9tico were playing without key players [[Diego Costa]], [[Juanfran (footballer, born 1985)|Juanfran]], [[Filipe Luis]] and [[Vitolo (footballer, born 1989)|Vitolo]], and in the 10th minute, [[Sime Vrsaljko]] was sent off with a red card, followed by Simeone being also sent off. Despite playing with ten men, without their manager at the bench, with most players in makeshift positions, and enjoying only 24% of ball possession, the team lost neither its shape nor its composure, eventually holding out to a 1\u20131 draw that was enough for them to progress to the final.<ref>http://www.football-lineups.com/match/285420/</ref> \u201cSimeone taught us to enjoy suffering,\u201d Arda Turan said in 2015, supporting this feeling that the Argentinean coach is a man who takes the best things out of bad situations.<ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/how-finishing-bottom-argentine-league-8062543</ref> Diego Godin has also said about his manager: \"\"The players would die for him [Simeone]. He gives belief that we can compete against much bigger teams. We have great confidence in him, we are with him to the death and also he with us - and that shows on the pitch. I believe the whole team has confidence in the coach and we all know the path we have to take: he marks the way for us and we go with him until the death. That is how you achieve things.\"<ref>http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3310/goal-50/2016/11/09/29340332/godin-were-with-simeone-until-the-death</ref><ref>https://www.scoopnest.com/user/ChampionsLeague/733260615314247680-godin-the-players-would-die-for-him-simeone-he-gives-belief-that-we-can-compete-against-much-bigger-teams</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSimeone's sons [[Giovanni Simeone|Giovanni]] and [[Gianluca Simeone|Gianluca]] are professional footballers, currently playing for [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia y Esgrima]] respectively.<ref name=\"50 best young footballers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/the-gentleman-ultra/2017/jan/24/50-best-young-footballers-italy-serie-a|title=The 50 best young footballers in Italy|publisher=The Guardian|author1=Blair Newman|author2=Luca Hodges-Ramon|author3=Richard Hall|author4=Franco Ficetola|author5=Mark Neale|author6=Emmet Gates|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Business Standard\">{{cite news|title=Gianluca Simeone, son of Atleti manager, signs with Argentine club|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/gianluca-simeone-son-of-atleti-manager-signs-with-argentine-club-119010801308_1.html|accessdate=9 January 2019|work=Business Standard|date=8 January 2019}}</ref> His third son, Giuliano, has been seen as a ball-boy for Atl\u00e9tico Madrid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/2015/01/08/en/football/spanish_football/1420675239.html|title=Who did Simeone celebrate the goals with?|last=MARCA.com|date=8 January 2015|website=MARCA|language=en|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{NFT |10041|name=Diego Simeone|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Super Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]]\n|[[1987\u201388 Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|1987\u201388]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|28||4||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|[[1988\u201389 Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|1988\u201389]]\n|16||2||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|[[1989-90 Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|1989\u201390]]\n|32||8||||||||||||||||\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!76||14||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Pisa Calcio|Pisa]]\n|[[1990\u201391 Serie A|1990\u201391]]\n|[[Serie A]]\n|31||4||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||4\n|-\n|1991\u201392||[[Serie B]]\n|24||2||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!55||6||2||0||0||0||0||0||57||6\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]\n|[[1992\u201393 La Liga|1992\u201393]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[La Liga]]\n|33||4||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||4\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 La Liga|1993\u201394]]\n|31||8||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||8\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!64||12||0||0||||||||||64||12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|[[1994\u201395 La Liga|1994\u201395]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|La Liga\n|29||6||8||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||37||8\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 La Liga|1995\u201396]]\n|37||12||8||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||45||12\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 La Liga|1996\u201397]]\n|32||3||3||0||2||0||7||4||44||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!98||21||19||2||2||0||7||4||126||27\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Inter Milan]]\n|[[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Serie A\n|30||6||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||1||41||7\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399]]\n|27||5||7||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||2||43||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!57||11||9||0||0||0||18||3||84||14\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n|[[1999\u201300 Serie A|1999\u201300]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Serie A\n|28||5||7||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0||47||7\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301]]\n|30||2||2||0||1||0||8||1||41||3\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Serie A|2001\u201302]]\n|8||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0||13||1\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Serie A|2002\u201303]]\n|24||7||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||0||34||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!90||15||12||2||1||0||32||1||135||18\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|[[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|La Liga\n|28||2||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||2\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 La Liga|2004\u201305]]\n|8||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||1||15||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Spain\n!36||2||5||0||0||0||6||1||47||3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|2004\u201305]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|17||2||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|2005\u201306]]\n|20||1||||||||||||||||\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!37||3||||||||||||||||\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!513||84||||||||||||||||\n|}\n\n===International===\nSource:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/simeone-intl.html |title=Diego Pablo Simeone \u2013 Century of International Appearances |publisher=Rsssf.com |date=15 June 2002 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]]\n|-\