center\"|5 || [[1970 FA Cup Final|1970 FA Cup Final replay]] || 28.49<ref name=\"BFI-1970s\" /> || {{dts|format=dmy|1970|April|29}} || BBC One/ITV\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|6 || [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Lady Diana Spencer]] || 28.40<ref name=\"BFI-1980s\" /> || {{dts|format=dmy|1981|July|29}} || BBC One/ITV\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|7 || [[Wedding of Princess Anne and Mark Phillips]] || 27.60<ref name=\"BFI-1970s\" /> || {{dts|format=dmy|1973|November|14}} || BBC One\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|8 || Prime Minister Boris Johnson's statement on COVID-19 || 27.1<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52018502 |title=PM's coronavirus address watched by 27.1m |date=2020-03-24 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-03-24 |language=en-GB}}</ref> || {{dts|format=dmy|2020|March|23}}  || BBC One/ITV/Channel 4/Sky News/BBC News\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|9 || [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] || 24.46<ref name=\"barb30\">{{cite web |title=Weekly top 30 programmes |url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30/ |website=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> || {{dts|format=dmy|2012|August|12}} || BBC One\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|10 || [[2012 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] || 24.24<ref name=\"barb30\"/> || {{dts|format=dmy|2012|July|27}} || BBC One\n|}\n\n''Notes'':\n*The [[Wedding dress of Princess Margaret|Wedding of Princess Margaret and Lord Snowdon]] (6 May 1960) was watched by an estimated 25 million viewers in Britain.<ref name=\"Princess Margaret and Lord Snowdon\">{{cite book |last=Wheen |first=Francis |last2=Fiddick |first2=Peter |title=Television: a history |date=1985 |publisher=Century Publishing |isbn=9780712609296 |page=229 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O8ZAAAAAMAAJ |quote=the wedding of Princess Margaret to Lord Snowdon in 1960 (watched by 25 million people in Britain and an estimated 300 million around the world)}}</ref>\n*At least two [[Muhammad Ali]] boxing matches were reported to have been watched by at least 26{{nbsp}}million viewers in the United Kingdom: the [[Fight of the Century|Fight of the Century (Ali vs. Frazier)]] was reported to have been watched by 27.5{{nbsp}}million British viewers in 1971,<ref>{{cite book|last=Green|first=Timothy|title=The Universal Eye: The World of Television|date=1972|publisher=[[Stein and Day]]|isbn=9780812814248|page=86|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSUvAAAAMAAJ&q=ali+frazier|quote=The annual Miss World Contest, which is often the single most popular program of the year \u2014 attracting half the British population \u2014 is a natural for BBC 1; so was the Ali-Frazier fight, which was watched by 27.5 million people.}}</ref> and [[The Rumble in the Jungle|The Rumble in the Jungle (Ali vs. Foreman)]] was reported to have been watched by 26{{nbsp}}million viewers on BBC One in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|title=Daily Mirror|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9tkZAQAAMAAJ&q=26+million|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=1 November 1974|quote='Ali is so tired he cannot raise his hands. ' The next moment Ali raised his fists and Foreman was knocked out. The 26 million who saw the same fight with the same commentary on BBC-1...did not hear that line. \"Yes, we cut it out, ' said a BBC man last night, 'to spare Harry Carpenter's blushes.'}}</ref>\n*[[Live Aid]] is reported to have reached approximately 24.5{{nbsp}}million British viewers in July 1985.<ref name=\"bafta\">{{cite news |title=Moments in TV History |url=http://www.bafta.org/heritage/features/moments-in-tv-history |work=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |date=19 November 2013}}</ref>\n*The [[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]] (29 April 2011) received a total audience peak of 26 million viewers, but this is a combined figure aggregated from the ten different channels that broadcast the ceremony. The highest figures of these were 13.59 million on BBC1, with an extra 4.02 million watching on ITV.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/resources/tv-facts/tv-since-1981/2011/events/ |title=TV Since 1981 |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board|BARB]] |accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Most-watched programmes====\nThe following is a list of most-watched programmes, excluding sporting events and news coverage. The mid-1980s introduction of in-week repeat showings accounts for six of the top ten programmes. On this measure, the 1996 Christmas edition of ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' is the most-watched non-repeated, non-documentary programme of all time in the UK. It is the third most-watched programme of all time on a single channel, after the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] and the [[wedding of Princess Anne and Mark Phillips]] in 1973 (see below).\n* Post-1981 figures verified by the [[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] (BARB)\n* Pre-1981 figures supplied by the [[British Film Institute]]\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!Show\n!Episode\n!Number of viewers<br> (millions)\n!Date\n!Network\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1 || ''[[EastEnders]]'' || [[Den Watts]] serves wife [[Angie Watts|Angie]] with divorce papers. || 30.15<ref name=\"BARB-1986\">{{cite web |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/resources/tv-facts/tv-since-1981/1986/top10/ |title=TV since 1981 \u2013 1986 \u2013 Top 10 programmes |publisher=Broadcasters' Audience Research Board (BARB) |accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> || {{dts|format=dmy|1986|December|25}}* || [[BBC One]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|2 || ''[[EastEnders]]'' || [[Michelle Fowler]] reveals that she is pregnant to [[Lou Beale]]. || 28.00<ref name=\"BARB-1987\">{{cite web |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/resources/tv-facts/tv-since-1981/1987/top10/ |title=TV since 1981 \u2013 1987 \u2013 Top 10 programmes |publisher=Broadcasters' Audience Research Board (BARB) |accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> || {{dts|format=dmy|1986|January|1}}* || [[BBC One]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|3 || ''[[Coronation Street]]'' || [[Hilda Ogden]] leaves, having appeared 