{"title_page": "Roanoke Review", "text_new": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = Roanoke Review\n| cover = \n| editor = Mary Crockett Hill\n| discipline = [[Literary journal]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language = English\n| former_names = \n| abbreviation = Roanoke Rev. \n| publisher = [[Roanoke College]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = Semi-monthly\n| history = 1967 to 2014 in print 2015 to present online\n| openaccess = \n| license = \n| impact = \n| impact-year = \n| website = http://www.roanokereview.org/\n| link1 = \n| link1-name = \n| link2 = \n| link2-name = \n| JSTOR = \n| OCLC = \n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = \n| ISSN = 0035-7367\n| eISSN = \n| boxwidth = \n}}\n\n'''''Roanoke Review''''' is an American literary journal based at [[Roanoke College]] in [[Salem, Virginia|Salem]], [[Virginia]].  It was founded in 1967 by Henry Taylor and Edward A. Tedeschi.  Among the journal's original contributors were [[Malcolm Cowley]], [[Lee Smith (author)|Lee Smith]], and [[R.H.W. Dillard]].   Robert Walter edited the Review until 2001.  Paul Hanstedt took over the Review after Dr. Walter's retirement, and has edited it since.  Starting in 2015, the Review became a digital-only journal, featuring stories, poems, nonfiction essays, interviews, art, and podcasts.<ref>\"Area Literary Journal is 30 Years Old,\" ''Roanoke Times'', September 13, 1998.</ref>\n\nAmong the review's recent contributors are Ernest Kroll, June Spence, [[Charles Wright (poet)|Charles Wright]] and [[Jacob M. Appel]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of literary magazines]]\n  \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.roanokereview.org/ ''Roanoke Review'' Website]\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:American bimonthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Roanoke College]]\n\n\n{{US-lit-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = Roanoke Review\n| cover = \n| editor = Mary Crockett Hill\n| discipline = [[Literary journal]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language = English\n| former_names = \n| abbreviation = Roanoke Rev. \n| publisher = [[Roanoke College]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = Semi-monthly\n| history = 1967 to 2014 in print 2015 to present online\n| openaccess = \n| license = \n| impact = \n| impact-year = \n| website = http://www.roanokereview.org/\n| link1 = \n| link1-name = \n| link2 = \n| link2-name = \n| JSTOR = \n| OCLC = \n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = \n| ISSN = 0035-7367\n| eISSN = \n| boxwidth = \n}}\n\n'''''Roanoke Review''''' is an American literary journal based at [[Roanoke College]] in [[Salem, Virginia|Salem]], [[Virginia]].  It was founded in 1967 by Henry Taylor and Edward A. Tedeschi.  Among the journal's original contributors were [[Malcolm Cowley]], [[Lee Smith (author)|Lee Smith]], and [[R.H.W. Dillard]].   Robert Walter edited the Review until 2001.  Paul Hanstedt took over the Review after Dr. Walter's retirement, and has edited it since.  Starting in 2015, the Review became a digital-only journal, featuring stories, poems, nonfiction essays, interviews, art, and podcasts. <ref>\"Area Literary Journal is 30 Years Old,\" ''Roanoke Times'', September 13, 1998. </ref>\n\nAmong the review's recent contributors are Ernest Kroll, June Spence, [[Charles Wright (poet)|Charles Wright]] and [[Jacob M. Appel]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of literary magazines]]\n  \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.roanokereview.org/ ''Roanoke Review'' Website]\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Virginia]]\n\n{{US-lit-mag-stub}}\n[[Category:Roanoke College]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roanoke_Review"}
{"title_page": "Potter's field", "text_new": "{{short description|Place for the burial of unknown or indigent people}}\n{{other uses|The Potter's Field (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by Jacob Riis.jpg|thumb|A trench at the potter's field on [[Hart Island, New York]], circa 1890 by [[Jacob Riis]]]]\n[[File:Dunn County Potter's Field graves.jpeg|thumb|Potter's field in [[Dunn County, Wisconsin]]]]\nA '''potter's field''', '''paupers' grave''' or '''common grave''' is a [[cemetery|place for the burial]] of unknown, unclaimed or [[indigent]] people.  \"Potter's field\" is of [[Bible|Biblical]] origin,<ref>Dictionary.com. Collins English Dictionary - Complete & Unabridged 10th Edition. HarperCollins Publishers. http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/potters field (accessed: December 24, 2014).</ref> referring to [[Akeldama]] (meaning ''field of blood'' in [[Aramaic]]), stated to have been purchased, with the coins that had been paid to [[Judas Iscariot]] for his identification of Jesus, after Judas' suicide, by the high priests of [[Jerusalem]]. The priests are stated to have acquired it for the burial of strangers, criminals, and the poor, the coins paid to Judas being considered blood money. Prior to Akeldama's use as a burial ground, it had been a site where potters collected high-quality, deeply red clay for the production of ceramics, thus the name potters' field.\n[[File:I come to claim my dead.jpg|thumb|\"I come to claim my dead\" drawing by [[William Thomas Smedley]], Circa 1884]]\n\n==Origin==\n{{Main|Akeldama}}\nThe term \"potter's field\" comes from [[Matthew 27:3]]\u2013[[Matthew 27:8|27:8]] in the [[New Testament]] of the [[Bible]], in which Jewish priests take [[Thirty pieces of silver|30 pieces of silver]] returned by a remorseful [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]]:\n\n{{quote|Then Judas, [[Kiss of Judas|who betrayed him]], seeing that he was condemned, repenting himself, brought back the thirty pieces of silver to the chief priests and ancients, saying: \"I have sinned in betraying innocent blood.\"  But they said: \"What is that to us?  Look thou to it.\"  And casting down the pieces of silver in the temple, he departed, and went and hanged himself with a halter.  But the chief priests, having taken the pieces of silver, said: \"It is not lawful to put them into the [[mite box|corbona]], because it is the price of blood.\"  And after they had consulted together, they bought with them the potter's field, to be a burying place for strangers.  For this the field was called Haceldama, that is, the field of blood, even to this day. \u2014 [[Douay-Rheims Bible]]}}\n\nThe site referred to in these verses is traditionally known as [[Akeldama]], in the [[Gehenna|valley of Hinnom]], which was a source of potters' clay. After the clay was removed, such a site would be left unusable for agriculture and thus might as well become a graveyard for those who could not be buried in an orthodox cemetery. This may be the origin of the name.<ref>R. T. France, ''The Gospel According to Matthew: An Introduction and Commentary'', Eerdmans (1985), p. 386{{ISBN?}}</ref> A field where potters dug for clay would also be \"conveniently already full of trenches and holes.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.common-place-archives.org/vol-06/no-04/bahde/|title=The Common Dust of Potter\u2019s Field|first=Thomas|last=Bahde|date=30 December 2016|publisher=|volume=06|issue=04|accessdate=30 December 2016|via=Common-Place}}</ref>\n\nThe author of Matthew was drawing on earlier Biblical references to potters' fields. The passage continues, with verses 9 and 10:\n\n{{quote|Then what the prophet Jeremiah had said came true: \"They took the thirty silver coins, the amount the people of Israel had agreed to pay for him, and used the money to buy the potter's field, as the Lord had commanded me.\"}}\n\nThis is based on a quotation from [[Book of Zechariah|Zechariah]] ({{Bibleref2|Zechariah 11:12\u201313}}). However, Matthew attributes the quote to Jeremiah. The author of Matthew may have been mistaken.  There are two other possible reasons for the reference.  First, Jeremiah also speaks of buying a field, in {{Bibleref2|Jeremiah 32:6\u201315}}. That field is a symbol of hope, not despair as mentioned in Matthew, and the price is 17 pieces of silver. The author of Matthew could have combined the words of Zechariah and Jeremiah, while only citing the \"major\" prophet. Secondly, \"Jeremiah\" was sometimes used to refer to the Books of the Prophets ''in toto''{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} as \"The Law\" is sometimes used to refer to Moses' five books &ndash; Genesis through Deuteronomy, the [[Pentateuch]].\n\n[[Craig Blomberg]] suggests that the use of the [[Blood money (term)|blood money]] to buy a burial ground for foreigners in [[Matthew 27:7]] may hint at the idea that \"Jesus' death makes salvation possible for all the peoples of the world, including the [[Gentiles]].\"<ref>[[Craig Blomberg|Craig L. Blomberg]], \"Matthew,\" in ''Commentary on the New Testament Use of the Old Testament'' (Grand Rapids: Baker Academic, 2007), 97.</ref> Other scholars do not read the verse as referring to Gentiles, but rather to Jews who are not native to Jerusalem.<ref>[[Raymond E. Brown|Brown, Raymond]]. ''The Death of the Messiah''. Yale University Press, Dec 1, 1998 p. 646</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n*[[Lincoln Park]], on [[Chicago]]'s [[North Side, Chicago|North Side]], found its origin in the 1840s as Chicago City Cemetery. The southernmost portion of the cemetery, where one may now find a number of baseball fields (north of LaSalle Dr., west of North Avenue Beach), was the location of the City Cemetery potter's field from 1843 to 1871. More than 15,000 people, including 4,000 Confederate soldiers, were buried here on marshy land near the water's edge. The baseball fields have occupied these grounds since 1877.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiddentruths.northwestern.edu/potter_field.html|title=Hidden Truths: Potter's Field|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Madison Square|Madison Square Park]], [[Washington Square Park]] and [[Bryant Park]] in [[New York City]] originated as potter's fields. The city's current potter's field, and one of the largest cemeteries in the United States with at least 800,000 burials, is on [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart Island]] in [[the Bronx]].<ref>Hart Island; Melinda Hunt and Joel Sternfeld; {{ISBN|3-931141-90-X}}</ref>\n*[[Hudson County Burial Grounds]]\n*[[Queen Lane Apartments]]. Work on the project was delayed by the discovery of a potter's field on an adjacent plot.\n*[[Washington Square (Philadelphia)]]\n*[[Washington Park (Albany)]] was the site of the State Street Burying Grounds, a municipal cemetery which included a potter's field. Some maps identify the section as the \"strangers\" burial ground.\n*[[Potter's Field (Omaha)]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n*[[Holt Cemetery]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]] contains the remains of known and unknown early jazz musicians, including [[Buddy Bolden|Charles \"Buddy\" Bolden]]. The battered remains of [[Robert Charles]], at the center of the 1900 [[Robert Charles Riots|New Orleans race riot]] were briefly interred there, then dug up and incinerated. It is located next to [[Delgado Community College]].\n*[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] had a potter's field at the corner of Yonge and Bloor Streets. The burial grounds were closed with some of the bodies moved to other cemeteries. Unknown number of bodies remained on the site when it was built over. Today the grounds are part of the posh [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville]] district, and the site of an office tower.\n* [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]], in the [[Anacostia]] area of [[Washington, D.C.]], contains remains of executed international spies including Nazi spies from [[Operation Pastorius]].\n* [[Cimeti\u00e8re de Laval]], near [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/091803/news1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515160907/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/091803/news1.html |archivedate=2008-05-15 }}</ref>\n* [[Music Hall (Cincinnati)|Music Hall]] in Cincinnati, Ohio was built over a nineteenth-century potter's field.\n* [[Eloise Cemetery]]\n\n== Popular culture ==\n{{in popular culture|date=March 2018}}\n*[[Hart Island, New York]], the Potter's Field in New York City, is featured in the film ''[[Don't Say a Word]]''. The independent documentary [http://www.brightcove.tv/title.jsp?title=1344621530  ''Hart Island: An American Cemetery'']{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by Melinda Hunt also concerns Hart Island.\n*It is now confirmed that the child actor [[Bobby Driscoll]] (''Peter Pan'', 1953) is buried in Potter's Field on [[Hart Island (New York)|Hart Island]] in New York, being unidentified at the time of his burial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themorningnews.org/archives/new_york_new_york/hart_island.php|title=Hart Island - The Morning News|first=Clay|last=Risen|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This is also loosely referenced in ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' in the episode \"Blasters\".\n*In the HBO drama ''[[Oz (TV Series)|Oz]]'', \"Potter's Field\" is the name for the cemetery where deceased prisoners with no next-of-kin or whose remains are unclaimed are buried.\n*In the 1953 film ''[[Pickup on South Street]]'', the character Moe Williams' (Thelma Ritter) sole motivation for work is to save money in order to prevent a possible burial in Potter's Field.\n*In Victor Hugo's ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'', Jean Valjean is buried in Potter's Field.\n*''[[From Potter's Field (novel)|From Potter's Field]]'' is a novel by [[Patricia Cornwell]].\n*''[[The Potter's Field (Peters novel)|The Potter's Field]]'' is the name of the seventeenth chronicle in the series of  ''[[Cadfael|Brother Cadfael]]'' detective books by [[Edith Pargeter|Ellis Peters]], later turned into a television episode.\n*''[[Potter's Field (comics)|Potter's Field]]'' is the title of a 3 issue limited comic book series (plus a one shot) written by [[Mark Waid]] and published by [[Boom! Studios]] about an anonymous investigator who takes it upon himself to discover the identities of those buried on Hart Island.\n*A potter's field is featured in [[Neil Gaiman|Neil Gaiman's]] novel ''[[The Graveyard Book]]''. One of the characters, Liza Hempstock, is a witch who was buried in a potter's field next to [[Nobody Owens]]' graveyard.\n*''[[Potter's Field (album)|Potter's Field]]'' is an album by the rock band [[12 Stones]].\n*\"No Eagle Lies in Potter's Field\" is the name of a song by the rock band [[On A Pale Horse]].\n*\"Potter's Field\" is the name of a song by the American [[Thrash metal]] band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] from their 1993 album ''[[Sound of White Noise]]''.\n*[[Railroad Earth]] has a song called \"Potter's Field\" on their self-titled 2010 album.\n*\"Potter's Field\" is a song by alternative band [[Mono Inc.]]\n*[[Tom Waits]] makes references to Potter's Field in several of his songs.\n*On the title track to [[Johnny Cash|Johnny Cash's]] album ''[[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]'', the lyrics include a reference to \"the potter's ground\" as a metaphor for dying without salvation.\n*In the long-running MUD ''[[GemStone IV]]'', an area called the \"Potter's Field\" is the primary spawn area for zombies.  The area's descriptions are, indeed, of a long-disused graveyard for the indigent and unknown.\n*Similarly, in ''[[City of Villains]]'' a massive graveyard called \"Potter's Field\" is a place where zombies spawn, while [[magic (paranormal)|magicians]] use the area for [[necromancy|necromantic]] rituals.\n*American [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] band [[Blue Highway]] mentions a Potter's field as Ottie's final resting place in the song \"Clay and Ottie\".\n*The name of the American [[noise rock]] band ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers]]'' describes a potter's field.\n*The Venture Compound in ''[[The Venture Brothers]]'' has a potter's field containing dead henchmen, as well as the bodies of a succession of clones Dr. Thaddeus Venture had made of his accident- and danger-prone sons.  Hank and Dean Venture remembered their father telling them to avoid a spooky house on the edge of their property, \"Mr. Potter's house\".  However the actual inhabitant, a reclusive scientist named Ben, told Dean Venture that no one named \"Mr. Potter\" had ever lived there, and theorized that Dean's father had actually called it \"potter's field\", because he and his father used the field in front of the house to bury the massive number of supervillains and henchmen who died on the compound over the decades, and hide the clone bodies to prevent others (including the Venture boys themselves) from learning that the original Hank and Dean were dead.\n*The term was used by [[Saul Berenson]] in the Series ''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]'' Episode 7 to describe where [[Raqim Faisel]] would be buried.\n*''[[Over the Garden Wall (TV series)|Over the Garden Wall]]'' features a town called Pottsfield, which is the residence of dead spirits.\n*In the novella ''[[Prisoner 489]]'' by [[Joe R. Lansdale]], in the potter's field behind the prison the headstones are only marked with the number in the order the condemned were executed.\n*In the film ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'', Potter's Field is [[Henry F. Potter]]'s housing development intended for those too poor to live in his slums. He eventually loses Potter's Field tenants to [[George Bailey (It's a Wonderful Life)|George Bailey]]'s nicer, more affordable Bailey Park.\n*[[Joanna Newsom]] makes reference to the term in the song Sapokanikan, from her album ''[[Divers (Joanna Newsom album)|Divers]]''.\n*\u2019The Potter\u2019s Field\u2019 is the title of one of the episodes from the fifth TV series of ''Montalbano.''\n*In the tenth episode of the fifth season of ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]'', \"When the World Went Away\" the character Root makes reference to \"the most principled corpse in Potter's Field.\" After her death, she is briefly interred in one (presumably Hart Island) before being disinterred in a search for her modified [[cochlear implant]].\n*The third act's climax of ''[[Gideon's Sword]]'' by [[Douglas Preston]] and [[Lincoln Child]] takes place on Hart Island. The book mentions the burial fields extensively. Preston has a blog post in their website about his own experience at Hart Island during a research trip.\n*Potter's Field is the location where Mike \"Meathead\" Stivic suggests to his father in law Archie Bunker to bury his Cousin Oscar in an episode of ''[[All In The Family]]''.\n*In the 2017 film, ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'', the character [[Kylo Ren]] informs [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] that her parents are buried in paupers' graves in the middle of the desert of the planet of Jakku.\n*In the 2017 musical, ''[[The View UpStairs]]'', the character Patrick refers to being buried in a Potter's field after being killed in the arson attack on the UpStairs Lounge.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Akeldama]]\n* [[Boot Hill]]\n* [[Mass grave]]\n* [[Pauper's funeral]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Common graves}}\n*[http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/html/hartbook2.html New York City's Hart Island Potter's Field ]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07103b.htm Haceldama] \u2013 From the Catholic Encyclopedia\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Potter's Field}}\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Place for the burial of unknown or indigent people}}\n{{other uses|The Potter's Field (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by Jacob Riis.jpg|thumb|A trench at the potter's field on [[Hart Island, New York]], circa 1890 by [[Jacob Riis]]]]\n[[File:Dunn County Potter's Field graves.jpeg|thumb|Potter's field in [[Dunn County, Wisconsin]]]]\nA '''potter's field''', '''paupers' grave''' or '''common grave''' is a [[cemetery|place for the burial]] of unknown, unclaimed or [[indigent]] people.  \"Potter's field\" is of [[Bible|Biblical]] origin,<ref>Dictionary.com. Collins English Dictionary - Complete & Unabridged 10th Edition. HarperCollins Publishers. http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/potters field (accessed: December 24, 2014).</ref> referring to [[Akeldama]] (meaning ''field of blood'' in [[Aramaic]]), stated to have been purchased, with the coins that had been paid to [[Judas Iscariot]] for his identification of Jesus, after Judas' suicide, by the high priests of [[Jerusalem]]. The priests are stated to have acquired it for the burial of strangers, criminals, and the poor, the coins paid to Judas being considered blood money. Prior to Akeldama's use as a burial ground, it had been a site where potters collected high-quality, deeply red clay for the production of ceramics, thus the name potters' field.\n[[File:I come to claim my dead.jpg|thumb|\"I come to claim my dead\" drawing by [[William Thomas Smedley]], Circa 1884]]\n\n==Origin==\n{{Main|Akeldama}}\nThe term \"potter's field\" comes from [[Matthew 27:3]]\u2013[[Matthew 27:8|27:8]] in the [[New Testament]] of the [[Bible]], in which Jewish priests take [[Thirty pieces of silver|30 pieces of silver]] returned by a remorseful [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]]:\n\n{{quote|Then Judas, [[Kiss of Judas|who betrayed him]], seeing that he was condemned, repenting himself, brought back the thirty pieces of silver to the chief priests and ancients, saying: \"I have sinned in betraying innocent blood.\"  But they said: \"What is that to us?  Look thou to it.\"  And casting down the pieces of silver in the temple, he departed, and went and hanged himself with a halter.  But the chief priests, having taken the pieces of silver, said: \"It is not lawful to put them into the [[mite box|corbona]], because it is the price of blood.\"  And after they had consulted together, they bought with them the potter's field, to be a burying place for strangers.  For this the field was called Haceldama, that is, the field of blood, even to this day. \u2014 [[Douay-Rheims Bible]]}}\n\nThe site referred to in these verses is traditionally known as [[Akeldama]], in the [[Gehenna|valley of Hinnom]], which was a source of potters' clay. After the clay was removed, such a site would be left unusable for agriculture and thus might as well become a graveyard for those who could not be buried in an orthodox cemetery. This may be the origin of the name.<ref>R. T. France, ''The Gospel According to Matthew: An Introduction and Commentary'', Eerdmans (1985), p. 386{{ISBN?}}</ref> A field where potters dug for clay would also be \"conveniently already full of trenches and holes.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.common-place-archives.org/vol-06/no-04/bahde/|title=The Common Dust of Potter\u2019s Field|first=Thomas|last=Bahde|date=30 December 2016|publisher=|volume=06|issue=04|accessdate=30 December 2016|via=Common-Place}}</ref>\n\nThe author of Matthew was drawing on earlier Biblical references to potters' fields. The passage continues, with verses 9 and 10:\n\n{{quote|Then what the prophet Jeremiah had said came true: \"They took the thirty silver coins, the amount the people of Israel had agreed to pay for him, and used the money to buy the potter's field, as the Lord had commanded me.\"}}\n\nThis is based on a quotation from [[Book of Zechariah|Zechariah]] ({{Bibleref2|Zechariah 11:12\u201313}}). However, Matthew attributes the quote to Jeremiah. The author of Matthew may have been mistaken.  There are two other possible reasons for the reference.  First, Jeremiah also speaks of buying a field, in {{Bibleref2|Jeremiah 32:6\u201315}}. That field is a symbol of hope, not despair as mentioned in Matthew, and the price is 17 pieces of silver. The author of Matthew could have combined the words of Zechariah and Jeremiah, while only citing the \"major\" prophet. Secondly, \"Jeremiah\" was sometimes used to refer to the Books of the Prophets ''in toto''{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} as \"The Law\" is sometimes used to refer to Moses' five books &ndash; Genesis through Deuteronomy, the [[Pentateuch]].\n\n[[Craig Blomberg]] suggests that the use of the [[Blood money (term)|blood money]] to buy a burial ground for foreigners in [[Matthew 27:7]] may hint at the idea that \"Jesus' death makes salvation possible for all the peoples of the world, including the [[Gentiles]].\"<ref>[[Craig Blomberg|Craig L. Blomberg]], \"Matthew,\" in ''Commentary on the New Testament Use of the Old Testament'' (Grand Rapids: Baker Academic, 2007), 97.</ref> Other scholars do not read the verse as referring to Gentiles, but rather to Jews who are not native to Jerusalem.<ref>[[Raymond E. Brown|Brown, Raymond]]. ''The Death of the Messiah''. Yale University Press, Dec 1, 1998 p. 646</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n*[[Lincoln Park]], on [[Chicago]]'s [[North Side, Chicago|North Side]], found its origin in the 1840s as Chicago City Cemetery. The southernmost portion of the cemetery, where one may now find a number of baseball fields (north of LaSalle Dr., west of North Avenue Beach), was the location of the City Cemetery potter's field from 1843 to 1871. More than 15,000 people, including 4,000 Confederate soldiers, were buried here on marshy land near the water's edge. The baseball fields have occupied these grounds since 1877.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiddentruths.northwestern.edu/potter_field.html|title=Hidden Truths: Potter's Field|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Madison Square|Madison Square Park]], [[Washington Square Park]] and [[Bryant Park]] in [[New York City]] originated as potter's fields. The city's current potter's field, and one of the largest cemeteries in the United States with at least 800,000 burials, is on [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart Island]] in [[the Bronx]].<ref>Hart Island; Melinda Hunt and Joel Sternfeld; {{ISBN|3-931141-90-X}}</ref>\n*[[Hudson County Burial Grounds]]\n*[[Queen Lane Apartments]]. Work on the project was delayed by the discovery of a potter's field on an adjacent plot.\n*[[Washington Square (Philadelphia)]]\n*[[Washington Park (Albany)]] was the site of the State Street Burying Grounds, a municipal cemetery which included a potter's field. Some maps identify the section as the \"strangers\" burial ground.\n*[[Potter's Field (Omaha)]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n*[[Holt Cemetery]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]] contains the remains of known and unknown early jazz musicians, including [[Buddy Bolden|Charles \"Buddy\" Bolden]]. The battered remains of [[Robert Charles]], at the center of the 1900 [[Robert Charles Riots|New Orleans race riot]] were briefly interred there, then dug up and incinerated. It is located next to [[Delgado Community College]].\n*[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] had a potter's field at the corner of Yonge and Bloor Streets. The burial grounds were closed with some of the bodies moved to other cemeteries. Unknown number of bodies remained on the site when it was built over. Today the grounds are part of the posh [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville]] district, and the site of an office tower.\n* [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]], in the [[Anacostia]] area of [[Washington, D.C.]], contains remains of executed international spies including Nazi spies from [[Operation Pastorius]].\n* [[Cimeti\u00e8re de Laval]], near [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/091803/news1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515160907/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/091803/news1.html |archivedate=2008-05-15 }}</ref>\n* [[Music Hall (Cincinnati)|Music Hall]] in Cincinnati, Ohio was built over a nineteenth-century potter's field.\n* [[Eloise Cemetery]]\n\n== Popular culture ==\n{{in popular culture|date=March 2018}}\n*[[Hart Island, New York]], the Potter's Field in New York City, is featured in the film ''[[Don't Say a Word]]''. The independent documentary [http://www.brightcove.tv/title.jsp?title=1344621530  ''Hart Island: An American Cemetery'']{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by Melinda Hunt also concerns Hart Island.\n*It is now confirmed that the child actor [[Bobby Driscoll]] (''Peter Pan'', 1953) is buried in Potter's Field on [[Hart Island (New York)|Hart Island]] in New York, being unidentified at the time of his burial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themorningnews.org/archives/new_york_new_york/hart_island.php|title=Hart Island - The Morning News|first=Clay|last=Risen|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This is also loosely referenced in ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' in the episode \"Blasters\".\n*In the HBO drama ''[[Oz (TV Series)|Oz]]'', \"Potter's Field\" is the name for the cemetery where deceased prisoners with no next-of-kin or whose remains are unclaimed are buried.\n*In the 1953 film ''[[Pickup on South Street]]'', the character Moe Williams' (Thelma Ritter) sole motivation for work is to save money in order to prevent a possible burial in Potter's Field.\n*In Victor Hugo's ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'', Jean Valjean is buried in Potter's Field.\n*''[[From Potter's Field (novel)|From Potter's Field]]'' is a novel by [[Patricia Cornwell]].\n*''[[The Potter's Field (Peters novel)|The Potter's Field]]'' is the name of the seventeenth chronicle in the series of  ''[[Cadfael|Brother Cadfael]]'' detective books by [[Edith Pargeter|Ellis Peters]], later turned into a television episode.\n*''[[Potter's Field (comics)|Potter's Field]]'' is the title of a 3 issue limited comic book series (plus a one shot) written by [[Mark Waid]] and published by [[Boom! Studios]] about an anonymous investigator who takes it upon himself to discover the identities of those buried on Hart Island.\n*A potter's field is featured in [[Neil Gaiman|Neil Gaiman's]] novel ''[[The Graveyard Book]]''. One of the characters, Liza Hempstock, is a witch who was buried in a potter's field next to [[Nobody Owens]]' graveyard.\n*''[[Potter's Field (album)|Potter's Field]]'' is an album by the rock band [[12 Stones]].\n*\"No Eagle Lies in Potter's Field\" is the name of a song by the rock band [[On A Pale Horse]].\n*\"Potter's Field\" is the name of a song by the American [[Thrash metal]] band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] from their 1993 album ''[[Sound of White Noise]]''.\n*[[Railroad Earth]] has a song called \"Potter's Field\" on their self-titled 2010 album.\n*\"Potter's Field\" is a song by alternative band [[Mono Inc.]]\n*[[Tom Waits]] makes references to Potter's Field in several of his songs.\n*On the title track to [[Johnny Cash|Johnny Cash's]] album ''[[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]'', the lyrics include a reference to \"the potter's ground\" as a metaphor for dying without salvation.\n*In the long-running MUD ''[[GemStone IV]]'', an area called the \"Potter's Field\" is the primary spawn area for zombies.  The area's descriptions are, indeed, of a long-disused graveyard for the indigent and unknown.\n*Similarly, in ''[[City of Villains]]'' a massive graveyard called \"Potter's Field\" is a place where zombies spawn, while [[magic (paranormal)|magicians]] use the area for [[necromancy|necromantic]] rituals.\n*American [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] band [[Blue Highway]] mentions a Potter's field as Ottie's final resting place in the song \"Clay and Ottie\".\n*The name of the American [[noise rock]] band ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers]]'' describes a potter's field.\n*The Venture Compound in ''[[The Venture Brothers]]'' has a potter's field containing dead henchmen, as well as the bodies of a succession of clones Dr. Thaddeus Venture had made of his accident- and danger-prone sons.  Hank and Dean Venture remembered their father telling them to avoid a spooky house on the edge of their property, \"Mr. Potter's house\".  However the actual inhabitant, a reclusive scientist named Ben, told Dean Venture that no one named \"Mr. Potter\" had ever lived there, and theorized that Dean's father had actually called it \"potter's field\", because he and his father used the field in front of the house to bury the massive number of supervillains and henchmen who died on the compound over the decades, and hide the clone bodies to prevent others (including the Venture boys themselves) from learning that the original Hank and Dean were dead.\n*The term was used by [[Saul Berenson]] in the Series ''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]'' Episode 7 to describe where [[Raqim Faisel]] would be buried.\n*''[[Over the Garden Wall (TV series)|Over the Garden Wall]]'' features a town called Pottsfield, which is the residence of dead spirits.\n*In the novella ''[[Prisoner 489]]'' by [[Joe R. Lansdale]], in the potter's field behind the prison the headstones are only marked with the number in the order the condemned were executed.\n*In the film ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'', Potter's Field is [[Henry F. Potter]]'s housing development intended for those too poor to live in his slums. He eventually loses Potter's Field tenants to [[George Bailey (It's a Wonderful Life)|George Bailey]]'s nicer, more affordable Bailey Park.\n*[[Joanna Newsom]] makes reference to the term in the song Sapokanikan, from her album ''[[Divers (Joanna Newsom album)|Divers]]''.\n*\u2019The Potter\u2019s Field\u2019 is the title of one of the episodes from the fifth TV series of ''Montalbano.''\n*In the tenth episode of the fifth season of ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]'', \"When the World Went Away\" the character Root makes reference to \"the most principled corpse in Potter's Field.\" After her death, she is briefly interred in one (presumably Hart Island) before being disinterred in a search for her modified [[cochlear implant]].\n*The third act's climax of ''[[Gideon's Sword]]'' by [[Douglas Preston]] and [[Lincoln Child]] takes place on Hart Island. The book mentions the burial fields extensively. Preston has a blog post in their website about his own experience at Hart Island during a research trip.\n*Potter's Field is the location where Mike \"Meathead\" Stivic suggests to his father in law Archie Bunker to bury his Cousin Oscar in an episode of ''[[All In The Family]]''.\n*In the 2017 film, ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'', the character [[Kylo Ren]] informs [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] that her parents are buried in paupers' graves in the middle of the desert of the planet of Jakku.\n*In the 2017 musical, ''[[The View UpStairs]]'', the character Patrick refers to being buried in a Potter's field after being killed in the arson attack on the UpStairs Lounge.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Akeldama]]\n* [[Boot Hill]]\n* [[Mass grave]]\n* [[Pauper's funeral]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Common graves}}\n*[http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/html/hartbook2.html New York City's Hart Island Potter's Field ]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07103b.htm Haceldama] - From the Catholic Encyclopedia\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Potter's Field}}\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potter%27s_field"}
{"title_page": "Latifiya", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Latifiya\n|native_name            = \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629\n|nickname               = \n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|image_seal             = \n|image_shield           = \n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Baghdad Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type2      = Municipality\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Mahmudiya District]]\n|government_type        = \n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = \n|leader_title1          = \n|leader_name1           = \n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           = \n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     = \n|established_date3      = \n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|area_total             = \n|TotalArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_land              = \n|LandArea_sq_mi         = \n|area_water             = \n|WaterArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban             = \n|UrbanArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_metro             =\n|MetroArea_sq_mi        =\n|population_as_of       = \n|population_footnotes   = \n|population_note        = \n|population_total       = \n|population_density     = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_density_mi2 = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_metro       = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_density_metro_km2 =\n|population_density_metro_mi2 =\n|population_urban       =\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             = \n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|32|58|55|N|44|21|33|E|region:IQ-NI|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes =\n|elevation              = \n|elevation_m           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n|twin1      =\n|twin1_country =\n}}\n\n'''Latifiya''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629}}), named after Latifiya river, is an [[Iraq]]i town south of [[Baghdad]], between [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiyah]] and [[Iskandariya]], inhabited originally by 97,043 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mmpw.gov.iq/uploads/image/Service%20Indicator/water/h/bag.jpg|title=\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0629 \u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f/ \u0646\u0633\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u062f\u0648\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0644\u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0627\u0647 \u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u0662\u0660\u0661\u0664|website=mmpw.gov.iq|access-date=2017-05-28|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160708112900/http://mmpw.gov.iq/uploads/image/Service%20Indicator/water/h/bag.jpg|archive-date=2016-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has a mix of Sunni and Shia Muslim population, and surrounded by in the west and the east by rural areas dominated by Sunni Arabs, while its countryside and towns to the north and south are Shia in their majority. \n\nDuring the period between 2003 and 2007, Latifiya was one of the most dangerous places for the [[Coalition Forces]]. The insurgent groups operated almost freely in Latifiya and the neighboring Sunni dominated [[Yusufiya]]. Nearly all the Shia citizens where ethnically cleansed, being chased off to [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiyah]], [[Nasiriya]] and [[Iskandariya]] nearby. They returned after the end of the civil war and the defeat of the Sunni by 2007. In 2014-15, the [[ISIS]] jihadists once again expelled the Shia population. With their defeat in 2017, once again the Shia returned, but this time it is the turn for the Sunni population to be harassed and deported.\n\nIt is home to the 1/4/6 Iraqi Army Battalion and US Patrol Base Latifiya (FOB ROW).\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Babil Governorate]]\n\n{{iraq-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Latifiya\n|native_name            = \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629\n|nickname               = \n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|image_seal             = \n|image_shield           = \n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Baghdad Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type2      = Municipality\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Mahmudiya District]]\n|government_type        = \n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = \n|leader_title1          = \n|leader_name1           = \n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           = \n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     = \n|established_date3      = \n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|area_total             = \n|TotalArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_land              = \n|LandArea_sq_mi         = \n|area_water             = \n|WaterArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban             = \n|UrbanArea_sq_mi        = \n|area_metro             =\n|MetroArea_sq_mi        =\n|population_as_of       = \n|population_footnotes   = \n|population_note        = \n|population_total       = \n|population_density     = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_density_mi2 = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_metro       = <!--Note: use population_footnotes for refs, use only unformatted numbers here -->\n|population_density_metro_km2 =\n|population_density_metro_mi2 =\n|population_urban       =\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             = \n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|32|58|55|N|44|21|33|E|region:IQ-NI|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes =\n|elevation              = \n|elevation_m           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n|twin1      =\n|twin1_country =\n}}\n\n'''Latifiya''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629}}), named after Latifiya river, is an [[Iraq]]i town south of [[Baghdad]], between [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiyah]] and [[Iskandariya]], inhabited originally by 97,043 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mmpw.gov.iq/uploads/image/Service%20Indicator/water/h/bag.jpg|title=\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0629 \u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f/ \u0646\u0633\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u062f\u0648\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0644\u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0627\u0647 \u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u0662\u0660\u0661\u0664|website=mmpw.gov.iq|access-date=2017-05-28|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160708112900/http://mmpw.gov.iq/uploads/image/Service%20Indicator/water/h/bag.jpg|archive-date=2016-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has a mix of Sunni and Shia Muslim population, and surrounded by in the west and the east by rural areas dominated by Sunni Arabs, while its countryside and towns to the north and south are Shia in their majority. \n\nDuring the period between 2003 and 2007, Latifiya was one of the most dangerous places for the [[Coalition Forces]]. The insurgent groups operated almost freely in Latifiya and the neighboring Sunni dominated [[Yusufiya]]. Nearly all the Shia citizens where ethnically cleansed, being chased off to [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiyah]], [[Nasiriya]] and [[Iskandariya]] nearby. They returned after the end of the civil war and the defeat of the Sunni by 2007. In 2014-15, the [[ISIS]] jihadists once again expelled the Shia population. With their defeat in 2017, once again the Shia returned, but this time it is the turn for the Sunni population to be harrassed and deported.\n\nIt is home to the 1/4/6 Iraqi Army Battalion and US Patrol Base Latifiya (FOB ROW).\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Babil Governorate]]\n\n{{iraq-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latifiya"}
{"title_page": "Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nAfter the initial [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)]], [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]], [[misinformation]], and [[disinformation]] emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and other aspects of the disease.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and misinformation can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of  countries such as [[China]], [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth|title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|accessdate=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word \u2018Coronavirus\u2019?|last=Putz|first=Catherine|website=thediplomat.com|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson |date= 8 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=2020-03-31|website=RSF|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria|date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |publisher=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |accessdate=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28<ref>.{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|accessdate = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation has been seen across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China and then later many of these same rumors spread to Korea and the United States prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |accessdate= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung|author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |accessdate= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |accessdate= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |accessdate= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included Russian state media ([[RT (TV network)|RT]] and [[Channel One Russia]]), the British tabloid ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', and right-wing media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|author= Sharma, Gouri | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020 the [[BBC]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that claimed the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal |first1=Kristian G. |last1=Andersen |first2=Andrew |last2=Rambaut |first3=W. Ian |last3=Lipkin |first4=Edward C. |last4=Holmes |first5=Robert F. |last5=Garry |title=The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2|journal=Nature Medicine|doi=10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9| date=March 17, 2020|pages=1\u20133 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4|doi-access=free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner|publisher=[[Live Science]]| accessdate =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"Racoon\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | date=January 29, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon,<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | accessdate=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while in the opinion of numerous medical experts there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese were using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|accessdate= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2020, ''[[The Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson | date=February 14, 2020 | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" /> \n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| accessdate=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|accessdate= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk |work=Asia Times|date=6 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russian accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archivedate=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] was very active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and many others. Sputnik branches in countries such as Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and Arab countries came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iranian accusation====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|accessdate=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|accessdate=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's \"Biological Attack\" Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the United Nations on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chinese accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2014 and misinformation \u2014 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest state-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=2020-04-05|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles claim that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|accessdate=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|accessdate=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippines====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master|date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|accessdate=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|Islamophobia}}\nIn India Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a religious gathering. <ref>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta|title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha|title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back To A Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha|title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen|title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|accessdate=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly|title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa|title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi|title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel|title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin|website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in an [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public\".<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by right-wing libertarians, NWO conspiracy theorists, and Christian Fundamentalists.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Accidental leakage==\n\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan_Institute_of_Virology#Concerns_as_source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]], among these is  that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cyranoski|title= Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens|date=February 22, 2017|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=592 | issue=7642 | pages= 399\u2013400| bibcode= 2017Natur.542..399C| doi= 10.1038/nature.2017.21487|pmid= 28230144|doi-access=free}}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> \n\nIt has also been claimed that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty |date=3 April 2020|work=National Review}}</ref> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media about that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate and was not patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=16 February 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | date=February 6, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | date=February 7, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao|accessdate=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington|website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu/> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=LAJKA |first1=ARIJETA |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical==\n{{See also|List of falsified medical products for COVID-19}}\n\nWidely circulated posts on social media have falsely claimed that, among other things:\n*'consuming boiled ginger with an empty stomach can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections|date=February 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'drinking lemon with water can be used to prevent the coronavirus and cancer, as it increases vitamin C levels',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online|date=March 10, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'holding one's breath for 10 seconds is an effective self-test for the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-viral-claims-holding-your-breath-can-test-covid-19 |title=World Health Organization refutes viral claims that holding your breath can test for COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'hot saunas and hair dryers can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hot-air-saunas-hair-dryers-wont-prevent-or-treat-covid-19 |title=Hot air from saunas, hair dryers won't prevent or treat COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'an ancient Sri Lankan drink can prevent the coronavirus'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-claim-ancient-medicinal-herbs-are-effective-coronavirus-remedy |title=Health experts refute claim that ancient medicinal herbs are an effective coronavirus remedy|date=March 17, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'Turmeric, salt, antiseptic and LifeBuoy brand soap'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2020/03/13/italy-indian-youth-swear-by-turmeric-crave-for-lifebuoy-to-keep-covid-19-at-bay.html |title=Indian youth swear by turmeric, crave for Lifebuoy to keep COVID-19 at bay|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Health authorities warn of false COVID-19 prevention tips online |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=2 April 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408120843/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*UV-C light, chlorine, and high (over 56&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures can be used on humans to kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-coronavirus-disinfectants|title=Misleading report claims UV light, chlorine and high temperatures can kill COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'gargling salt water, drinking hot liquids like tea and avoiding ice cream can stop the transmission of COVID-19'<ref>{{cite news |title=Health authorities warn of false COVID-19 prevention tips online |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=2 April 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408120843/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Fake guidelines on Facebook, claiming to be from a Chinese doctor, stated that red soap is more germicidal than soaps of other colors and white handkerchiefs can cause a 'harmful effect' on coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title='Red soap, white handkerchiefs': experts refute misleading coronavirus prevention 'tips' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/red-soap-white-handkerchiefs-experts-refute-misleading-coronavirus-prevention-tips |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=18 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321124738/https://factcheck.afp.com/red-soap-white-handkerchiefs-experts-refute-misleading-coronavirus-prevention-tips|archivedate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Homeopathic medicine [[Arsenicum album]] is claimed as an \"add on\" to prevent COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Menon |first1=Shailesh |last2=Thacker |first2=Teena |title=Can 'Ars Alb-30' protect you from Covid-19? AYUSH Ministry thinks so |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/pharmaceuticals/can-ars-alb-30-protect-you-from-covid-19-ayush-ministry-thinks-so/articleshow/74945805.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Advice for staying at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19 were circulated on Facebook and WhatsApp.<ref>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=26 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archivedate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=20 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*  Making masks out of wet-wipes  was suggested as an alternative to surgical masks on Facebook.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wet wipes not recommended for use as DIY coronavirus protection masks |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/wet-wipes-not-recommended-use-diy-coronavirus-protection-masks |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* A video for preparing hand sanitizer at home for prevention of COVID-19, by  mixing rum, bleach and fabric softener  circulated on the internet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health experts warn against mixing rum, bleach and fabric softener to make 'hand sanitiser' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-warn-against-mixing-rum-bleach-and-fabric-softener-make-hand-sanitiser |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=30 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402224042/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-warn-against-mixing-rum-bleach-and-fabric-softener-make-hand-sanitiser|archivedate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Another post appeared, claiming that [[Tito's Vodka]] could be used in an effective homemade hand sanitizer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10news.com/news/fact-or-fiction/fact-or-fiction-titos-vodka-can-be-used-in-hand-sanitizer|title=Fact or Fiction: Tito's Vodka can be used in hand sanitizer?|date=2020-03-10|website=KGTV|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n* Exposure to sunlight, drinking warm water or heating to {{convert|26|\u2013|27|C|F}} will kill the virus. UNICEF officials refuted the false claims that they released coronavirus prevention guidelines, and the afromentioned claims were included in the fake claims supposedly released by the UNICEF. <ref>{{cite news |title=UNICEF officials refute false claim that agency released coronavirus prevention guidelines |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/unicef-officials-refute-false-claim-agency-released-coronavirus-prevention-guidelines |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=10 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330130059/https://factcheck.afp.com/unicef-officials-refute-false-claim-agency-released-coronavirus-prevention-guidelines|archivedate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll of the above claims have been disproven; for example, ginger has not been proven to cure any viral illness, and vitamin C has also not been proven to be effective against the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine cure===\n\nSeveral viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a PSA debunking this claim, as did the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac|website=Pedestrian.TV|accessdate=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===African resistance===\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|accessdate=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=7 April 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=7 April 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\n===5G===\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates|accessdate=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his allegations went viral;<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> both the claims and the video, which were endorsed by singer [[Keri Hilson]], were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne}}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] have had to resort to posting pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were torched, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \u201cjust nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\u201d<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref>  [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> <ref>https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/</ref>\n\n[[YouTube]] announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been promoted, among others, by [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref><ref>https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers</ref>\n\nBy 6 April 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to 6 April.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\nIn India, a false rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Methanol===\nIran has reported [[methanol]] consumption incidents under the false belief that it would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Rum-running|bootleg alcohols]] that contain methanol, which is an industrial alcohol, were often consumed since [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story on British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of [[ethanol|alcohol]]-based [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac|date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise ship safe from infection===\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Scientists caution that this is possible, but not guaranteed.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on Feb. 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>\n\n===Country-based===\n\n====Australia====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=25 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archivedate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur|date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine Tamiflu, according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|accessdate=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina|date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | accessdate=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis|website=heise online|language=de|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Parliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on \u2018clapping vibrations destroy virus potency\u2019 after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the World Health Organization warned against eating  cabbage  to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=31 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archivedate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe poisonous  fruit of the [[Datura]]  plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding preventing COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous \u2018remedy\u2019 for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=www.thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming \u2018coronavirus shaped\u2019 datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=7 April 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n*An \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress  was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight prevent the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0CVP\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|accessdate=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |publisher=Factcheck.afp.com |date=2020-02-21 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\n\nAccording to a survey research conducted by  IPSOS, 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing wuzu/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation) cannot infect anyone and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is Sunnah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=25 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archivedate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Sri Lanka====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)| cannabis ]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannbis in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-19|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol| CBD oil ]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas|website=Forbes|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n\nClaims that  Vitamin D pills  could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=2020-02-27|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]],  a chemical used in some industrial aplications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|accessdate=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz| title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren| title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\"/> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=9 April 2020| accessdate=9 April 2020 | publisher=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason|date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe  US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the  [[Hoover Institution]] who in series of articles  consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions In Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=April 2020}} For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City,  claimed that it was a mis-perception that the disease \"hangs in the air\" as it \"takes direct person-to-person contact\", \"If you're under 50 and you're healthy, (...) there's very little threat\". He pledged to keep schools open, even if pupils are sick. He declined to cancel St. Patrick's Day parade and then did. He resisted calls to cancel regular street sweeping and then did. He gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David|date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Presidential====\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal|date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palca|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number.\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson|website=USA Today|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus in order to destabilize the administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|accessdate=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49591617778).jpg|thumb|240px|President Trump speaks during a press briefing on the COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", senior health official Anthony Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time. The [[Associated Press]] estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> However, Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27 and it was announced on April 8 that GM would produce 30,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] for $489.4 million by the end of August, with production to start the week of April 12 and the first 6,132 ventilators being delivered by June 1. It was the first Defense Production Act contract for ventilators and GM confirmed it was not profiting from it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|work=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for $489.4 million|date=April 8, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Ford partnered with [[General Electric]] and converted its auto plant in [[Rawsonville, Michigan]] to ventilator production in early April and promised to deliver 50,000 by July 4, scaling up production to 7,000-7,200 a week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|work=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] on December 30, 2019 revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|accessdate=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|accessdate=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later research published on January 20, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|accessdate=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|accessdate=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|accessdate=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|accessdate=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng|url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=CounterPunch|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref> and [[Asia Times|''Asia Times'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe|date=2020-03-17|website=Asia Times|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus \u2018may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic\u2019|date=2020-03-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> who criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith}}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau - Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|work=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\n\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]].{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Russian===\n\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb - BBC News |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmenistan ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use Of The Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=NPR.org |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use Of The Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=2020-03-31 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; RSF|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until 25 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|accessdate=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson|date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al|website=Barron's|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about the inadequacies in the working conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1=Carville |first1=Olivia |last2=Court |first2=Emma |last3=Brown |first3=Kristen V |title=Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website=Bloomberg | date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Collman |first1=Ashley |title=Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website=Business Insider |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who?|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll|title=Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first=Caroline|last=Orr|date=April 1, 2020|website=National Observer|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> \n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry |first=Terry Jr. |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned [[China News Service]] debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[Humpback whale|humpback whales]] allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=2020-04-05|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in [[Moscow]] was passed around as if it were true.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===UK \u00a320 banknote===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknote]]s contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nAfter the initial [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)]], [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]], [[misinformation]], and [[disinformation]] emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and other aspects of the disease.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and misinformation can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of  countries such as [[China]], [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth|title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word \u2018Coronavirus\u2019?|last=Putz|first=Catherine|website=thediplomat.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson |date= 8 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=2020-03-31|website=RSF|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria|date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |publisher=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28<ref>.{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation has been seen across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China and then later many of these same rumors spread to Korea and the United States prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung|author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included Russian state media ([[RT (TV network)|RT]] and [[Channel One Russia]]), the British tabloid ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', and right-wing media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|author= Sharma, Gouri | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020 the [[BBC]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that claimed the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal |first1=Kristian G. |last1=Andersen |first2=Andrew |last2=Rambaut |first3=W. Ian |last3=Lipkin |first4=Edward C. |last4=Holmes |first5=Robert F. |last5=Garry |title=The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2|journal=Nature Medicine|doi=10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9| date=March 17, 2020|pages=1\u20133 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4|doi-access=free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner|publisher=[[Live Science]]| accessdate =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"Racoon\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | date=January 29, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon,<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | accessdate=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while in the opinion of numerous medical experts there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese were using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2020, ''[[The Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson | date=February 14, 2020 | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" /> \n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk |work=Asia Times|date=6 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russian accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archivedate=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] was very active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and many others. Sputnik branches in countries such as Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and Arab countries came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iranian accusation====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's \"Biological Attack\" Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the United Nations on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chinese accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2014 and misinformation \u2014 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest state-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=2020-04-05|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles claim that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|accessdate=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|accessdate=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippines====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master|date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|Islamophobia}}\nIn India Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a religious gathering. <ref>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta|title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha|title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back To A Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha|title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen|title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly|title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa|title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi|title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel|title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin|website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in an [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public\".<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by right-wing libertarians, NWO conspiracy theorists, and Christian Fundamentalists.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Accidental leakage==\n\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan_Institute_of_Virology#Concerns_as_source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]], among these is  that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cyranoski|title= Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens|date=February 22, 2017|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=592 | issue=7642 | pages= 399\u2013400| bibcode= 2017Natur.542..399C| doi= 10.1038/nature.2017.21487|pmid= 28230144|doi-access=free}}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> \n\nIt has also been claimed that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty |date=3 April 2020|work=National Review}}</ref> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media about that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate and was not patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=16 February 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | date=February 6, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | date=February 7, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao|access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington|website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu/> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=LAJKA |first1=ARIJETA |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical==\n{{See also|List of falsified medical products for COVID-19}}\n\nWidely circulated posts on social media have falsely claimed that, among other things:\n*'consuming boiled ginger with an empty stomach can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections|date=February 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'drinking lemon with water can be used to prevent the coronavirus and cancer, as it increases vitamin C levels',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online|date=March 10, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'holding one's breath for 10 seconds is an effective self-test for the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-viral-claims-holding-your-breath-can-test-covid-19 |title=World Health Organization refutes viral claims that holding your breath can test for COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'hot saunas and hair dryers can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hot-air-saunas-hair-dryers-wont-prevent-or-treat-covid-19 |title=Hot air from saunas, hair dryers won't prevent or treat COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'an ancient Sri Lankan drink can prevent the coronavirus'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-claim-ancient-medicinal-herbs-are-effective-coronavirus-remedy |title=Health experts refute claim that ancient medicinal herbs are an effective coronavirus remedy|date=March 17, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'Turmeric, salt, antiseptic and LifeBuoy brand soap'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2020/03/13/italy-indian-youth-swear-by-turmeric-crave-for-lifebuoy-to-keep-covid-19-at-bay.html |title=Indian youth swear by turmeric, crave for Lifebuoy to keep COVID-19 at bay|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Health authorities warn of false COVID-19 prevention tips online |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=2 April 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408120843/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*UV-C light, chlorine, and high (over 56&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures can be used on humans to kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-coronavirus-disinfectants|title=Misleading report claims UV light, chlorine and high temperatures can kill COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'gargling salt water, drinking hot liquids like tea and avoiding ice cream can stop the transmission of COVID-19'<ref>{{cite news |title=Health authorities warn of false COVID-19 prevention tips online |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=2 April 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408120843/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-authorities-warn-false-covid-19-prevention-tips-online|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Fake guidelines on Facebook, claiming to be from a Chinese doctor, stated that red soap is more germicidal than soaps of other colors and white handkerchiefs can cause a 'harmful effect' on coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title='Red soap, white handkerchiefs': experts refute misleading coronavirus prevention 'tips' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/red-soap-white-handkerchiefs-experts-refute-misleading-coronavirus-prevention-tips |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=18 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321124738/https://factcheck.afp.com/red-soap-white-handkerchiefs-experts-refute-misleading-coronavirus-prevention-tips|archivedate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Homeopathic medicine [[Arsenicum album]] is claimed as an \"add on\" to prevent COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Menon |first1=Shailesh |last2=Thacker |first2=Teena |title=Can 'Ars Alb-30' protect you from Covid-19? AYUSH Ministry thinks so |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/pharmaceuticals/can-ars-alb-30-protect-you-from-covid-19-ayush-ministry-thinks-so/articleshow/74945805.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Advice for staying at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19 were circulated on Facebook and WhatsApp.<ref>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=26 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archivedate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=20 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archivedate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*  Making masks out of wet-wipes  was suggested as an alternative to surgical masks on Facebook.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wet wipes not recommended for use as DIY coronavirus protection masks |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/wet-wipes-not-recommended-use-diy-coronavirus-protection-masks |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* A video for preparing hand sanitizer at home for prevention of COVID-19, by  mixing rum, bleach and fabric softener  circulated on the internet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health experts warn against mixing rum, bleach and fabric softener to make 'hand sanitiser' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-warn-against-mixing-rum-bleach-and-fabric-softener-make-hand-sanitiser |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=30 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402224042/https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-warn-against-mixing-rum-bleach-and-fabric-softener-make-hand-sanitiser|archivedate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Another post appeared, claiming that [[Tito's Vodka]] could be used in an effective homemade hand sanitizer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10news.com/news/fact-or-fiction/fact-or-fiction-titos-vodka-can-be-used-in-hand-sanitizer|title=Fact or Fiction: Tito's Vodka can be used in hand sanitizer?|date=2020-03-10|website=KGTV|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n* Exposure to sunlight, drinking warm water or heating to {{convert|26|\u2013|27|C|F}} will kill the virus. UNICEF officials refuted the false claims that they released coronavirus prevention guidelines, and the afromentioned claims were included in the fake claims supposedly released by the UNICEF. <ref>{{cite news |title=UNICEF officials refute false claim that agency released coronavirus prevention guidelines |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/unicef-officials-refute-false-claim-agency-released-coronavirus-prevention-guidelines |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=10 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330130059/https://factcheck.afp.com/unicef-officials-refute-false-claim-agency-released-coronavirus-prevention-guidelines|archivedate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll of the above claims have been disproven; for example, ginger has not been proven to cure any viral illness, and vitamin C has also not been proven to be effective against the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine cure===\n\nSeveral viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a PSA debunking this claim, as did the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac|website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===African resistance===\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=7 April 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=7 April 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\n===5G===\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his allegations went viral;<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> both the claims and the video, which were endorsed by singer [[Keri Hilson]], were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne}}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] have had to resort to posting pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=3 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were torched, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \u201cjust nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\u201d<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref>  [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> <ref>https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/</ref>\n\n[[YouTube]] announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been promoted, among others, by [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref><ref>https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers</ref>\n\nBy 6 April 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=6 April 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to 6 April.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\nIn India, a false rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Methanol===\nIran has reported [[methanol]] consumption incidents under the false belief that it would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Rum-running|bootleg alcohols]] that contain methanol, which is an industrial alcohol, were often consumed since [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story on British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of [[ethanol|alcohol]]-based [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac|date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise ship safe from infection===\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Scientists caution that this is possible, but not guaranteed.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on Feb. 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>\n\n===Country-based===\n\n====Australia====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=25 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archivedate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur|date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine Tamiflu, according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|accessdate=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina|date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis|website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Parliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on \u2018clapping vibrations destroy virus potency\u2019 after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the World Health Organization warned against eating  cabbage  to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=31 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archivedate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe poisonous  fruit of the [[Datura]]  plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding preventing COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous \u2018remedy\u2019 for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=www.thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming \u2018coronavirus shaped\u2019 datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=7 April 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n*An  \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress  was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight prevent the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |publisher=Factcheck.afp.com |date=2020-02-21 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\n\nAccording to a survey research conducted by  IPSOS, 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing wuzu/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation) cannot infect anyone and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is Sunnah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=25 March 2020 |language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archivedate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Sri Lanka====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)| cannabis ]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannbis in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-19|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol| CBD oil ]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n\nClaims that  Vitamin D pills  could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=2020-02-27|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]],  a chemical used in some industrial aplications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz| title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren| title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\"/> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=9 April 2020| access-date=9 April 2020 | publisher=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason|date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe  US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the  [[Hoover Institution]] who in series of articles  consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac|website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions In Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=April 2020}} For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City,  claimed that it was a mis-perception that the disease \"hangs in the air\" as it \"takes direct person-to-person contact\", \"If you're under 50 and you're healthy, (...) there's very little threat\". He pledged to keep schools open, even if pupils are sick. He declined to cancel St. Patrick's Day parade and then did. He resisted calls to cancel regular street sweeping and then did. He gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David|date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Presidential====\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal|date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palca|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number.\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson|website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus in order to destabilize the administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49591617778).jpg|thumb|240px|President Trump speaks during a press briefing on the COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", senior health official Anthony Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time. The [[Associated Press]] estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> However, Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27 and it was announced on April 8 that GM would produce 30,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] for $489.4 million by the end of August, with production to start the week of April 12 and the first 6,132 ventilators being delivered by June 1. It was the first Defense Production Act contract for ventilators and GM confirmed it was not profiting from it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|work=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for $489.4 million|date=April 8, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Ford partnered with [[General Electric]] and converted its auto plant in [[Rawsonville, Michigan]] to ventilator production in early April and promised to deliver 50,000 by July 4, scaling up production to 7,000-7,200 a week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|work=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] on December 30, 2019 revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later research published on January 20, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng|url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=CounterPunch|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and [[Asia Times|''Asia Times'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe|date=2020-03-17|website=Asia Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus \u2018may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic\u2019|date=2020-03-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> who criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith}}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau - Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|work=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\n\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]].{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Russian===\n\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb - BBC News |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmenistan ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use Of The Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=NPR.org |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use Of The Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=2020-03-31 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; RSF|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until 25 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|accessdate=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson|date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al|website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about the inadequacies in the working conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1=Carville |first1=Olivia |last2=Court |first2=Emma |last3=Brown |first3=Kristen V |title=Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website=Bloomberg | date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Collman |first1=Ashley |title=Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website=Business Insider |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who?|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll|title=Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first=Caroline|last=Orr|date=April 1, 2020|website=National Observer|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> \n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry |first=Terry Jr. |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned [[China News Service]] debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[Humpback whale|humpback whales]] allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=2020-04-05|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in [[Moscow]] was passed around as if it were true.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===UK \u00a320 banknote===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknote]]s contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[